\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid5178298 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have any brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, there was eight in the family really. Yes. An
d - my - one brother died. And the first recollect - remember - I remember my mother's funeral. And I wonder if you remember - well you wouldn't of course - the horses wore plumes. And - they were covered with a - black velvet clothes. And of course there
 
was no motor cars. Therefore the - it was very slow. And - I remember I was - oh I should think, I was four year old, and I had a white frock on and I remember a black sash, and a white bonnet with black and white streamers. And then - well it - of course
 
we all split up then when mother - yes, all - some went to aunts, some went to friends and - I went to an aunt, and - she lived with my grandmother, that would be her mother of course and - we lived in a flat in London, which is Peabody Buildings, I don't
 
know - you've heard of that haven't you. Yes, probably Buildings. I don't know whether it's still there now, but - you - it was four stories up and all the - stairs were - stone. And - on the top was flat, the roof was flat. And also there was - rooms - o
f
 this size. There'd be about six up there. For each landing I suppose, and a - gran always - gran used to do her washing off there, there were wash houses and - wooden rolling - wringers and suchlike and us children used to play up there, of course, and -
 
there was walls dividing each - block of flats and there was a - a gap in between that us children used to go from one flat to the other, playing - down one flight of stairs. And of course our favourite game was sliding downstairs, being - stone they got 
-
 smooth. And - then on bonfire night we used to go up there and watch the fireworks from Crystal Palace, we could see that. We'd stand on chairs. Oh wonderful. There was - Prince of Wales feathers I can remember and - there was a huge boat, I think that w
a
s Nelson's - Victory, and the King and Queen, portrait of the King and Queen. What else do I remember? Emblems. The different emblems from the Empires. And then at school we used to do a bit - which they don't do now. It was Empire Day. They don't celebra
t
e Empire Day like we used to do. Each class had had - would represent a colony belonging to the British Empire. I remember ours was Australia. And as far as possible each child was - had a - something to represent the dress of that colony. And then - on -
 
say about twelve o'clock, midday we'd go out into the playground and the Union Jack would be - hoisted, and the girls would curtsey, and the boys would salute the flag. And then we'd all - get into our classes again, and each class would sing the anthem t
o that - or what do you call another name for an anthem?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You mean the song of the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. For each part of that colony. Like Wales they'd sing - what is that one now? Land of my father's, that's right, and - Scotland'd be - not Bon
ny Charlie, not that one - oh dear - I can't remember now - no, no, no that's not the one - oh I've got it on my own one had but anyway - that's - that was done and then we used to have half day. Holiday. That's what we used to look forward to. And - afte
r that I went to - Blackfriars, in London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The first Peabody Buildings was in Canning Town did you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, that was at - Blackfriars. That's right, yes. Peabody Buildings - was - was where I lived with grandma, and then my father, he lived in P
onsonby Buildings which is the next block - in the next street. Ponsonby Buildings. And we lived right up at the top. The last but one - flat. And from our window - we could see the railway this side, and then - all along here would be the arches where th
e
 - railway horses and railway vans used to be stored. And then - my sister was a cripple, the one next to me, and I used to have to take her to this corner of the street and the - the carriage used to come and taker her - a horse and carriage used to come
 and pick the crippled children up to take them to a special school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was quite advanced for that time wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. And I was allowed special - permission to be late from school when it was my turn to go and take her to - to this corn
er of the street. So of course I didn't mind that. But we always used to have - my aunt that I lived with from - when I left grandma - always sent me to a - church school, you see, and nowadays, I don't whether they do now but we always had arithmetic - s
c
ripture lessons to start with. Started with a hymn. And - I don't know whether they do now but that's always - always a - always our - being a church school naturally we would. Saints days we'd have a half day - to go to church. And go from the school, yo
u had to congregate at the school to start with and then we marched from school to the church, which - which was nearest to that school you see. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Would you have a sort of service there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, a little service at the church. Last abo
ut half an hour I should imagine. And then we had the day off. And that's - that's where we used to get the holidays that they get today in a different way. And - I can remember seeing a balloon on top of this flat - while we were playing one day there wa
s a balloon went over, and it wasn't until - what they call the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 zeppelins}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 , that style of thing, but round. With a basket underneath. Yes. That's right. And we could see the people in them. We used to wave to the people, we used to think - wonder if they'l
l ever come back down. You know, we used to think - as children we used to think they'd never come down again and we used to watch them 'til they were right out of sight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was it just a sort of pleasure outing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's all, yes. Often there'd be o
bservatory - weather balloons go over but they more or less it was - you could see the people in the baskets. And what amused us too - the different clothes they used to wear. I can remember my grandmother wearing a bonnet, and a - a shawl with sequins al
l at the - edging, and - long dresses of course naturally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What colour did your grandmother wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Mostly black. Mostly black. With lace all round the edge of - cape. And of course child like I used to put this bonnet on. Yes. And - mostly in the
 evenings we used to sit by the fire and grandma'd let me - comb her hair, she had lovely long hair, and I'd roll it up all in little curls, Merry Widow curls, if you got tired and worried she'd say, come on, she said, comb my hair for me, and she'd sit o
n her little chair and there I'd be doing this - doing her hair and - thinking I was great you know. And - of course auntie used to go out to work. She used to work at - the White Hart in London - that was a - hotel. She was a cook. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that all day or evenings as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All day. She'd be home about six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She didn't do any evening work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. No. And I can remember - coming from school, if I was late, I was very bad at arithmetic at school, real duffer. If we had four s
ums I'd get one wrong - one right at the most. But anyway - gran had a dog, big collie dog, and - she always used to come and meet me, twelve o'clock, she'd be at - and of course I usually had to be kept in - for my sums, you see, to get my - correct my a
r
ithmetic. And they'd say, your dog's waiting for you. And - of course we used to get the cane too. Oh yes. Yes. That's the only thing I used to be caned for. Arithmetic. And I used to cry the minute was over - when the board used to be turned up - she say
s, you can put your handkerchief away, we've not started yet. Oh I used to be terrified.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you always caned if you got a sum wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Caned and - any misbehaviour whatever we did. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But that was the only thing you were caned for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's all I had cane for, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Were there any other punishments they used to give you and the other children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well - sometimes they'd put you say it was summertime, they'd put you inside the fireguard and make you stay th
ere - and not go out to play. And - of course we used to get poor children as well - in the class. And they were very - good to those, they used to - some of them used to come without shoes on. I can remember that. And they used to give shoes - out to the
se poor children, and we also had a penny bank. Each child took a penny each week, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You each had your own penny bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did the poor children manage to bring a penny or not do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, some di
dn't. Those that couldn't do it didn't used to bother. And - I didn't. 'Cos father was often - more or less out of work often. Yes. Yes, my father was more or less out of work. And in this flat I can remember - it isn't very nice to remember but - all we 
h
ad as one room - at the top of this flat and I - there was an alcove which took a double bed. And there was a couch there, there was couch there and a couch there. And my crippled sister used - sleep on the couch, but my eldest sister and I used to sleep 
on chairs. Wooden chairs, wooden - kitchen chairs, that's all we had to sleep - father on that couch and my eldest brother on that couch and of course my crippled sister had the other couch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about the alcove with the double bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well that - 
we hadn't any mattress - so we couldn't use it. No, it wasn't used, it was just curtained off, that's all. You see? And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
You say your father and your crippled sister and yourself, what about your grandmother and your aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ah, they lived in the other block of flats in the next street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You didn't actually live with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 For part time - part time, but not - not - not for very long, you see. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Most of your childhood you were living with your father were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 With my fathe
r. And then - I went with gran for a certain time. And that's where - I - we - I saw most of the - street vendors and that sort of thing. With my gran, yes. I suppose that was holiday times more or less, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You'd go to her in the holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Because your father was at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's it. Yes. And - well he used to go out to find work. He more or less - used to come up to - oh dear, dear, that fish market. That's right, Billingsgate. And - what's that other one - Covent G
arden, used to go there. He used to go out early in the morning you see, and - I can remember the muffin man used to come round on a Sunday. And - oh the - the Sundays were very quiet. No playing in the streets or anything like that. Oh no, we were never 
allowed in the streets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there children playing in the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. Very seldom. Very very seldom. No, we were always kept quiet on a Sunday and - no sewing. No sewing. Oh no, mustn't - mustn't get a needle. No. Whatever we could do without 
we used to do without on Sunday. I used to go to church. And then - Sunday school in the afternoon. Then back again home. Then after tea you'd hear the muffin man come round, he'd have a green }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 baize}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  apron on with a tray on his head and ring this - huge bel
l. Of course we used to go out then - there were six muffins for a penny. And then there'd be the watercress barrows. Do you remember the barrow - you wouldn't remember the barrows, you'll have seen the pictures of them, barrow boys. Yes. That's right. We
ll they used to come - bring watercress, shrimps, winkles and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was mainly on a Sunday that they would come was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, in the week as well. Yes. In the week as well but - chiefly on Sunday was the muffin man, the shrimps and the winkles, and 
watercress and that sort of thing. But in the week there'd be the catsmeat man, there'd be the coalman used to call and - you could buy your coal by the bucketful. I don't know how much it was but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your gran do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. And salt. They use
d to have huge lumps of salt, the size of this table, and - so in depth, and you could buy a pennyworth, whatever you could afford. And milk used to come round - at your door, in a big iron - zinc can - can.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Churns were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, cans. And there
'd be ladles, ladle - ladle it into your jug - jug, whichever you wanted, half pint or - I felling it used to be gill then. Gills and quarts and pints. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Baker coming round too was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, we used to go to the dairy for the baker. Dairy -
 sell milk as well there of course and butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about rag and bone men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. That's right, and chairs to mend and knives to grind - and scissors. And what was the other one we used to have - I remember my first roundabout. And I had to just 
go in this room and it'd hold three - six children. And the man used to work it with a handle. And for a penny each - they would have about six rounds, then the cord would run out - when the - the rope would run out that was your end and you'd come off. S
ix.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that at an amusement park or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, in the street. Yes, in the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I've never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I have never seen one since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How did he transport it, did it sort of wheel along?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 On a cart. On a cart. On
 the cart and then he'd sat it up in the street and - of course we all used to rush out, oh - the round about man, we used to say. 'Course I used to run gran. She'd give me a ha'penny for that. A ha'penny that was. And - but the catsmeat man used to tickl
e me, it was - he'd come round with a - huge I don't know whether you've seen the - baskets that the bakers would use, or - or the butchers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Flattish baskets that you have over your arm do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, big flattish baskets. Well the ca
tsmeat man'd have one of those on his arm, he'd wear a green - white and blue apron, butcher's apron, and a straw hat and he - and on the - in his basket he'd have about six slices of meat, horseflesh I suppose it was, on skewers. And it was penny - penny
 
a skewer. Well of course gran had always got a cat, and a dog, so of course I used to go down to get two. And the cats that used to follow. I remember one day - sticks in my mind now as old as I am, there was two dogs came out and wanted to join the queue
.
 There was big cats, little cats, all sorts of cats, all colours, and these dogs - of course the cats wouldn't have it and there was a real fight. And people were throwing buckets of water over them to stop them fighting. But - that's one I remember but t
h
e lavender lady too. The lavender lady. She'd got a basket and - can't - don't you see them in the picture. Long apron and - oh we used to get round her because - she'd give you a bit - if any - any of the heads used to fall off, which they used to often 
-
 little - little heads of lavender, she'd throw them out of the basket and us children used to gather them up, and make little lavender - little lavender bags with them. And sell them for a ha'penny. Oh yes, yes. I've done that, yes. And another thing we 
used to do - we used to go round to the pawnshop, you've heard of the pawnshop, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There still are a few.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, I think so. Where the three balls hung up. And - we got - used to get fed up sometimes naturally, and we used to make our own amusem
ent those days, not like they are now. We used to go round to this - this pawnshop and as the people came out, you'd - they'd pick out the pins you see, the things were all bundled up, weren't tied up, they were - fastened with pins. And we'd gather these
 
pins up and put them on a bit of paper, then we'd go home - and make little windmills - and chalk on the corners of the windmills and make them all pretty colours and sell them for - some sweet money. Because we never used to get - pocket money those days
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You didn't get any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. Oh no, I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did you sell those little windmills for, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh ha'pennies and farthings. Oh yes. And - of course you could get a farthings worth of sweets then, we used to get
 about - six aniseed balls for a farthing. Yes. I can remember my - my brother coming home from the war - what was he in now - the - the - Ninth Hussars I think it was - had brass - oh wonderful brass braid on and - and - a plumed hat and sword, I've know
n him to come in home and he gave me sixpence. Oh, I thought I was - oh marvellous, to have a sixpence. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That would have been the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes, he was in - he was in for - twenty-five years. He passed away last - yea
r. Yes. He was gassed two or three times and - and he was in the Cavalry. And - oh yes, it affected his health naturally and - of course I was quite proud going down the street - with my brother. Everybody was looking and - and - I can remember writing co
m
petitions at school too, when I left - when I left gran's we went to my aunt in Bishopsgate - fire station, had a - I expect you remember - it's there still now isn't it. Opposite the Liverpool Street Station. Ah yes. Opposite the railway station. And the
r
e was ten - taxi ranks all along those days, when they were just coming in the taxis and we thought oh wonderful to watch them. And - the horses used to be - there was no - no - what shall I say - engines - engines those days but all horses. And - for - w
h
en uncle was on duty in the watch room there'd be this big - switchboard, and - a bell used to ring and he'd put this switch down when there was a call for fire and that used to unhook the horses harness at the back in the stable, and of course the horse 
- horses used to come out then and go in their own places, so of course they were trained, naturally, came in their places and the - then the - whoever was - in charge of - would hook the harness onto the shafts and one thing and another. And I remember -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you watch that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. We were allowed to do it, we were allowed to play in the yard. And when we heard this bell go we knew there was a - fire. And there was a - a mark, us children were allowed not to come over that mark. But we could watc
h went on and I remember I was in the - engine room, as we used to call it, and I went to run out into the yard, to get onto my - our place where - safety - safety line they used to call it, and my dress got hooked up on the hooks where the - they have th
e
ir - helmets and coats and suchlike. And luckily it was an empty one. But there I hung - there I hung 'til the - men and the doors were all open and the men had gone. And uncle was in the watchroom luckily that day and he came and got me off. Took me off.
 These horses were passing me at a furious - furious - the bodies passing me as they were coming but they never bothered. Never hurt me mind you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You must have been frightened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I was frightened, yes. But - of course I used - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was when you were staying with that aunt and uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 My uncle - that's right, Uncle Arthur, he was the fireman you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was he an uncle by marriage or your own uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, a real uncle. Oh yes, yes. And I remember coming down the - when I was li
ving with auntie - when uncle was off - off duty, he'd sleep upstairs in their own little flat - rooms, we had four rooms there, and - I was allowed - I used to sleep on the floor that - week, he would do a week alternate you see, week on and a week off. 
A
nd - when there was a fire - and they wanted extra - firemen, the bell - used to ring up on the - just above the door and a light used to go on. And if uncle didn't hear it. I used to have to go and wake him up. And he always had his boots - and jacket al
l
 ready, 'cos his helmet and - and - belt with his - the hatchet on was always downstairs. But I remember I used to have to clean his - boots, big boots they used to wear in these days, and all the brass button. I had six coats to do every night. Put the -
 button on a - proper - button - button - brace as well call it, clean them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Is that something that keeps the button away from the cloth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, it's a sort of a wooden - or - or you can get brass ones or you used to have the wood ones, and you jus
t slide the buttons on, the fixed buttons, and of course you could clean them without spoiling the - cloth, you see. And same with the number. You put - the numbers you put that under a - number and clean that, I had that to clean, those to clean and his 
boots. Every night. And if you went out, if it was his day off and you went out and wore his private shoes - I had those to do every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you get on well with your uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh - no, not that uncle, I did with auntie, I had the best of attenti
on there. Had best of everything. Clothes and everything. Food -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She was nice was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, food and - oh - always had fruit on the sideboard and everything which I didn't have at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Fruit on the sideboard must have been rare at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh it was - always. It was rare, yes. I can remember a lemon always being on the sideboard. Uncle was very fond of lemon. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So he'd have quite a well paid job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, he was fire - he was an officer. You see. And - until he got 
hurt in a fire and then of course he had to come out. But I had the best of attention - best of - living there. Which was a direct contrast at home. You see, until father got out of work again, father couldn't afford to pay me - pay auntie. And home I had
 to go again. Yes. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He used to pay for your keep did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. When he could. When he could. And then - from there we went to - Plaistow. Ann Street, Plaistow, I don't know whether you know Plaistow. Yes. Yes. We used to live in James
 Street. Another aunt used to live in Balaam Street. Where the swimming baths used to be, I don't know whether they're still there. Uncle - that uncle was a wheelwright. Ah - a big church. Yes, we used to pass that. I can remember the - the - the baths - 
t
hat's right, I have swum in there. I don't know whether - it's still there is it? Oh and uncle lived up - opposite the - swimming baths. He was the wheelwright. That was Uncle Arthur. He was a wheelwright, whether they're still there or not I don't know, 
I'd love to go back and see it. And - oh yes. I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You went there then when your father couldn't afford to pay your aunt any more?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
I had to go home again you see then. Yes, yes. Yes, and - stayed there and - pretty rough of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What was your father's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well he was a - he used to work for - first - on a pantechnicon, what they used to call a removal then, but they were called pantechnicons then, for Mr Neville. And then from there he went onto a brewers dray, you know the huge b
arrels with these horses, he had lovely horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Driving the dray and loading and unloading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Four horses. Oh yes. And we had a lot of - lots of brasses because on winter days us children used to - have them on the table in - and play hoop-ka
 with them. And another time - another game we used to play, we used to take the leaf off the table and play slides like the - have the slides today, we used to make our own slide with this - leaf of the table. But - to get back from - to Plaistow. That w
a
s another rough - place. Oh there used to be fights next door. People used to fight and - and I can remember nursing one - Mrs Lawrence - she used to let us have two rooms, father and - my brother and I. My other sisters had all left. Two of them had gone
 to an orphanage. And others had gone out, I don't know where they'd gone. They were in -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about your crippled sister, was she in the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, she was taken away to - Whipps Cross, Leytonstone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that to a foster home or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. To hospital. Because when I came home from school - everywhere was all sealed up. And I said to Mrs Lawrence, I said, where'd Dolly? So she said, oh she's been taken away, been taken away to hospital, she's got T.B. In those days they used to
 - I don't know what they used to call it - fumigate it sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Get rid of all the germs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. 'Cos everywhere was sealed up, the doors and everything, windows all sealed up. And - she never came home again. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you never see her again then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I seen her - I saw her about - six years ago when she was in Denmark Street. There was a convalescent home there. And during the war they were sent down to - Kent. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So it was pretty rough in Plaistow was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Very - from there - my brother and I used to have one - we used to sleep upstairs and father used to sleep downstairs in the front room. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There'd be just the two rooms then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He was more or less out of work all the - on and 
off. And I can remember often we used to go to school without any meals. Without a breakfast. Until we got in touch with a - I don't know whether it was a mission or what it was. Or belonged to the Salvation Army. But we - we children used to line up and 
- go into a big hall and they'd give - there was wooden }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 forms}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 and you'd all sit on these forms and - there'd be sheets, hymn sheets put up, and we'd sing hymns 'til the coffee - we used to have - cocoa, we used to have a mug of hot cocoa and a bun given us.
 And that was our breakfast. Otherwise we'd got to school with nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And that was before school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Before school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Saturdays and Sundays too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. No, not Sundays. No. We used to have nothing on Sunday. We had bread and dripp
ing, if there was any bread in the house we used to have bread and dripping. I used to run errands to get some dripping. I - yes, come home and get a basin and get some dripping. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You'd run errands for a neighbour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, anybody. And - or ru
n another errand for some bread. And run another errand and we used to - if - another day an - an errand - and we used to get - huge bags of broken biscuits, that was our dinner. That was our dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Where did you get those from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Any - any shop. Any shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have to pay anything for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Whatever we earnt - by - running errands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was your payment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. I remember in flats there was an old lady, and my eldest sister looked after her in the - when she come ou
t of school at half past four, but when she couldn't do it I used to go down - and I'd only be about six I should imagine or seven, and - she'd always have the door open, she was always in bed, very old lady. Old to me naturally. She must have been bedrid
d
en anyway, she was always in bed, and no light. Only a candle. And we'd light the fire and then go - run any errands. And wait 'til her son used to come home. Then her son used to take over and I used to go upstairs and look after my crippled sister then.
 Until she was taken away of course. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Her son would give you something for your trouble would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. The week - at the weekend, we used to do that every day, and then he'd give you about fourpence weekly, that was a lot of money then. Yes, I used to give it to my - eldest sister and she'd buy some food for the weekend them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was she the one that did the buying and planning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Oh she was still at school. Yes, she wasn't fourteen then. And then she used to go to laundry classes and she used to take our clothes to wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She looked after all that did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Gran used to do the - sheets, and that. When we had sheets. Often we didn't have sheets, there was just - no blankets, we used to have coats. Those were the very poor times of course but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
But when you were in Plaistow you must have been a long way from your gran then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes. And I can remember - when I lived at gran's - she'd say - when I lived with Aunt Emily I mean in the fire station, an
d she'd say, now I'm going to take you to grandma's today. This was on a Wednesday. She'd take me one Wednesday and she'd point out different - different adverts and different - buildings, say, now you get to that building then you go to the next building
,
 and then the next week I'd have to go on my own. And take this little - basket of goodies to grandma. Tea and a little cake and such like and butter. And I used to walk all the way. All the way from - from Bishopgate to Blackfriars. Yes. But if it was ra
i
ning - I'd give a ha'penny on the bus. We used to have ha'penny - horse bus riding. And I used to love to go upstairs because I could just look over the bar, and watch the horses, so I wasn't very old, I could just look over that bar and see the horses, a
nd used to charge me a ha'penny and if it rained - used to have a little apron, little waterproof apron over your - knees then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 To keep you dry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was open upstairs wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. No cover. And the trams were open as well too. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How old were you when you were there do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I'd be about - six or seven. All round about that age and - and father then - was - driving cabs, hansome cabs they used to call them then. Where the driver - sat right 
up top. And he'd open a little - a little - window like that and look at - at the fare, whoever was insider and say, where to madam? And he often used to say - come home and he had layers and layers of - paper - newspaper to keep in dry and warm in the wi
n
ter. But - I can remember a story he used to tell me, when he was on the brewers drays, and you know they used to get terrible fogs in London. And - one night he couldn't - he couldn't see where he was going, so he said, I let the reins go, and he said, h
ome to the horses, and the horses took him home, to the yard where - where they belonged. Let them go. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What were you saying about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
The children - babies didn't used to have - dummies like they have today. They used to have a li
ttle - sugar - tied up in a - a liner - just in a piece of lines, and they used to such that. And the babies bottle were no - weren't the same as they are today, they were - sort of - do you remember the - soldier's bottles, water - drinking bottles?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The curved shape?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. This - this way - pear shaped. And they'd have a - two - two tubes, glass tubes in them, and the long - rubber tube to the baby's mouth, and the mothers could put the bottle in the pram and leave the baby to feed itsel
f. I can remember those. Also the prams are not - weren't the same as they are today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What were they like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
They were - basket work. Basket - chair. You know like the - you know like the bedroom chairs - like that and they were back to back, the 
seats would be back to back. My sister one side and I the other, and then there was two long handles and two long iron legs. So that they didn't fall over. I've never seen one since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about wheels then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was two big wheels, just two big
 wheels. Two big wheels. And one little - one - bar at the - at the back and these two at the front, and then these two long handles. And I've never seen one since. And another thing I remember - they don't - didn't used to have ambulances like they do to
d
ay. There used to be - now what can I say - a place similar to a coalbunker, well there'd be a stretcher - in there, kept in that. Mind you it wasn't - it wasn't stone, it was wooden. We used to call it the stretcher hut. And for - different streets, so m
a
ny - one to so many streets. And then - if there was an accident or anybody taken ill in the street or whoever was on duty, policeman, would go and fetch this stretcher. And it had a hood on. Just at this end it had a hood on for the head part. And - they
 broke the - whoever - got the stretcher out had to pick this person up and run them to the hospital, there was no ambulance then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you ever remember seeing drunk and disorderly people carried off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. I was terrified. That was one - in
 the streets - there was one - often - that was very often, they would come down the street and I used to rush upstairs to gran.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that the same with all the places you lived, there was a lot of that?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. I can remember gran - e
very - every evening she'd take her jug and go up to the Noah's Ark, I don't know whether you'd remember - you remember that, on Blackfriars Road. Noah's Ark, she used to go up with her jug and - and those days they used to give them clay pipes if they ha
d
 - regular customers, clay pipes, or they give them a piece of cheese, and often she'd bring that piece of cheese home for me, to put on a piece of bread and put it in the oven, of course they were open stoves, not like gas stoves or anything of these day
s, and I'd put that on a plate, enamel plate in the oven and then I'd do her hair. Play with her hair. 'Til it was ready. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did she like to drink, would she have beer or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ordinary beer, just dark - beer. I don't know whether it
 was stout or - it was dark beer because I know - she used to put it on the table and - I was - I was very naughty, I used to take - like vinegar, those days, which I shouldn't do, naturally and I thought, oh this is vinegar. But oh it - it was beer. She 
s
aid, that'll teach you - not to - not to steal. I can remember that. Oh the hop pickers, do you remember the - the - Londoners, that was their holiday. Main holiday, to go hop picking. And - yes, I was with Mrs Lawrence then. And she wanted me to go with 
h
er. But father wouldn't let me go. I don't know why but he - no, he says, you're not going. And - we used to like to watch them, we used to - all line up at the street us children who didn't go, and of course brakes used to take them then or carts, whiche
v
er you - they could manage. Whichever they were - rich enough to own. And - they'd have their bundles, not - not suitcases like today, they'd be bundles of clothes. With the babies and - and dogs and cats used to go with them, the birds. Everything used t
o
 be loaded onto these carts and - brakes. And they'd be singing away and - you know, half of them would be drunk before they started the journey. Yes, it was a yearly - yearly holiday for then. And of course nowadays they have - proper chalets and suchlik
e
, but they didn't those days. They had - made their own tents and - what have you. Anything, sleep on the floor, any - anything. So of course that's why father wouldn't let me go. But - oh dear. And when they came back, oh the noise. It used to be terrifi
c. Used to go on right 'til - oh three o'clock in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Would they be singing and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Singing and - and - coming home you see, the carts were rumbling along the roads. And there'd be no sleep that day, that - the weekend wh
en they come home. And then another thing I remember - if anybody was very ill in that street - they'd put straw down on the street. On - on the floor, so that the - the horses and carts didn't make a noise. Yes. I used to - I asked that, I said, why - wh
at are you putting the straw down for? Oh so and so's very ill, got to be quiet. So you see it was all cobblestones and - and the horses make a noise. But you don't see that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember wreathes outside people's doors if they collected money f
or a wreath if anybody in the street had died?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I don't remember that. No I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember pictures of the Virgin Mary outside Catholic households at certain times of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ah there was in - now I - now you've
 - brought that to mind, in - my - our house was the - centre one in the street. Well that had a plaque - of people that were - that had passed away. Yes. And I can remember - saying - oh look, there's mother's name there. And - whether that's plaque's st
ill there or not, it wasn't a wreath or anything, or the Virgin Mary, it wasn't a - a grotto as we called it. No. Or a - a - image.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just a plaque with names of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Of those that had - and - and everybody used to collect. Everybody. And - peop
le used to stand still then as the funeral went passed. Nowadays they don't. And the gentlemen always took their hats off. And we always stood and waited 'til it had passed. And then they'd say, you can go now. And - we always had black bordered - when th
ere was a - postman used to come and there was a black bordered envelope, we used to say there was - somebody had died. And we used to have black bordered }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 
handkerchiefs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  too. They don't have that now do they? No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When your mother died you wouldn't have gone to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. I can remember being in the carriage. Yes. And sitting on somebody's - one of our auntie's laps, I don't know which one. And I said, what are you crying for? And they says, hush child, hush child, I can remember them saying 
that. And I can remember - standing at the graveside. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you go back to your home afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. And from there I suppose I must have gone to another aunt. But I don't remember much about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember if there were a lot of people at the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, the room was quite full, there was one from New Zealand, my Aunt Ada. She had little - Ronnie then. He had pink eyes and yellow hair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Sort of Albino?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right. And - we used to say - used to say to 
him, haven't you got lovely hair - 'cos we were all very dark as children, very dark. And he was the only one - fair one in the family. But she - I know she came from - New Zealand. And my sister Ada - which is now, she's still alive, and she went out to 
N
ew Zealand to her. And she's still out in New Zealand. But she's a widow now of course. And her family's grown and gone away. But - let's see if I can remember something else. Oh, and the games. Different games to what they play these days. They had - tip
 - cat. Boys used to have tip-cat. The boys - you had a - a stick about so long, and - tapered off at each end, and then the boys had a big stick - I'd say about - so big. And then - about six inches.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And-the second one about two foot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. A
ll depends on the height you were, if you had a tall boy you had a - a bigger one. And you'd hit - they'd hit this - one end and then it used to fly. And see who could hit - hit it the furthest. Whichever could make it go the furthest. And the girls used 
to have wooden hoops and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 boys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 used to have iron ones. And the girls used to have wooden - handles to hit theirs this way, and the boys used to have wooden handles with a - wire hook, - and hook theirs onto the - hoop and run along with theirs. And I cou
ldn't make that out as a child, say - why do they have their - why can't we have the same as the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did they say to you when you said that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh you're a girl, you're a girl. They can't do it like we can. And then - French skipping. Girls 
used to do French skipping. That's a - a very long rope, and - you wind it round two girls, and you - this fashion - one - one hand and then the other hand, 'til you had two - two ropes going each - at the same time. One, one, and jumping each - jump over
 each - rope. It was very difficult 'til you got used to it. You got used to the rhythm, you see. We used to call that French skipping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did boys skip too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well very often, but not in the double - not in the French skipping, they had the single on
e but not the - not the - double. And then we used to play - fivestones. I don't know whether they still do that. Fivestones. You have a little ball about so big, and - fivestones, square stones, they were made in - made, you could buy them, set - in the 
s
hops. Fivestones you'd call them. And you'd - throw the ball up, and drop the ball - drop - drop the stones. And then you throw the ball up again and catch one, two, three, four. And then you'd catch them on your hand. One two, three, four, all the way al
ong, and then you'd - throw the ball up, one. Throw the ball up again and catch it. You see, until you - you stopped where you - you let the ball drop, that was - you're out. And the next one's turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you throw the ball up really high?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, oh 
no. No, on the floor, we used to play it on the floor. Throw about as high as this table. So that you - to give you time to catch up one - pick up one stone. And then throw the ball up again -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Get as many stones as you could until the ball came down again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Came down - and you - if you missed the ball you were out, you see, and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You had to catch the ball as it came down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, each time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you'd only pick up one stone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 At a time. And then the next time, if you h
ad picked them all up - and - without letting the ball drop. You started again and picked up two at a time. And then the next time you'd pick up three. And the next time you'd pick up the four, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There must have been quite a lot of skill in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh it was very interesting because you all had to take your turn. Then -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did a large group play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, six of us used to play in the road, we used to sit in a round ring on the floor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All having your turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right. Yes. Yes. Another -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you keep a score then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. Oh the eldest girl used to say - oh you're on number two, you're on number four or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Somebody kept count?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes. And another game we used to play was - swings. There was n
o going to the swing park or anything like that, those days - we had lamps. 'Cos the streets were lit lamp - by lamp. And you know the bar? Well there used to be a bar where the - man used to put his ladder, if anything went wrong, and - but this bar, we 
used to throw the rope over that, and we used to swing round the lamp post and on - that was our swing. And another game - the boys used to play - what's that other one? Statues. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The sort of statues they play today at birthday parties and that kind of thing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, you all stand in a - and you - you - hold your hand and pull that person, and as you - as you are - left, you - so you stand, say you were thrown out and you were on hand then you've got to stand like that. And whoever posed the bes
t - gave the best - pose won the game. Then there's another one, learn the trade. You don't hear of that these days. They had - one girl stood one end, and the - you had stood - the others stood in a row. And these in the row'd say, please we've come to l
earn the trade, to this person at the other end. She'd say, what trade? We'd say, any trade. She said, set to work and do it. And we'd say - beforehand we'd say, well now what are we going to do this time. Be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 shoe cleaners}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 . Then we'd all start shoe - shoe -
 imitating cleaning our shoes, and then she'd say - and if she - guessed it we'd all have to run back home. Whoever was caught had to go and stay with her. And then - so forth, 'til we were all caught. That was another game.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that just girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, boys used to play it too. Yes. Yes. Boys, yes, boys used to play. And - what other games - let me see. Oh when I was with - with gran, we used to have a happy evening - Friday evenings, we used to go to - we used to call it the Institute, well it'd b
e like - well they have evenings out now like the Brownies do. Assembly room. And you'd play games and - there was somebody in charge naturally, and we used to get up little plays. And I was always picked for a Japanese or a - we had a - season play and I
 was Autumn, being dark, and I was a pansy. I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have lines to say or was it mainly mimed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh mimed. Except for one part, we - I was picked as a Japanese. And then we had to dance and a fan dance. And singing, and fan dancing and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Would you rehearse this and put it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. People used to come, I can remember people used to sit that end and we used to do - dressing up, National costumes. Lovely, and used to have our hair done and little roses each - each side and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were at Blackfriars that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your gran come and watch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. My sister. My eldest sister used to come - and watch that. She used to think it fine fun to think her sister was there. And
 - but for Christmas we used to have one - one - party, that was at school - when father was out of work. And I know one Christmas we didn't know it was Christmas. My brother and I, all the others had gone, there was just my little brother and I left, wit
h father. And all we knew was Christmas we used to pull - pull - t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 the ends of the newspaper - and make our chains of that and - we - we - I lost - I know I lost the key, front door key one night - one day. And we had to wait 'til - oh - I think father ca
me in about eight o'clock. It was wintertime, cold. And we stood over a grating outside a - a - what do they call them - well it'd be a caf\'e9
 now, they call them cafes then, you could go in and buy - say fish and chips or you could buy a sausage and mash an
d - what did they used to call it, pease pudding and - faggots and all that sort of thing. And - we used to stand there to keep warm, then we'd go along - a little way further along the street and to a toy shop, and we'd say, now wouldn't I like one of th
ose, I'd like so and so, I'd like that lovely doll. And then when we got too cold we'd go back to this - to get warm again 'til father came home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you waiting ther}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8995913\charrsid675430 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  then do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh about two or three hours, we were home from s
chool - 'til father come home at eight o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And that was at Christmastime was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Christmastime, I can remember it was Christmas time because - often it used to be snowing. So it would be Christmastime and - all the toys were - you know, the streets were all lit up you see, for the - wke say - what will - would I like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there no where else you could have gone to wait?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well we didn't know anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There wasn't a neighbour who kept an eye on you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No. No. T
hat's a dreadful place that was, I'll tell you where that was. That's at Gibson Street, near Shadwell. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was it very rough then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. There was - oh then we had - we had two rooms, but - the people - there was - there was only one toilet for the whole block of flats. And it was - dreadful, there was no bath or nothing, no hot water or nothing - nothing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there just a communal tap to share with the other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. And there was fighting every Saturday night. And we used to 
put a - I remember we used to put - father's coats over the - letterbox so as they wouldn't - look in. Yes, screaming murder and - oh I used to be terrified.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you ever left alone there at night when your father was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not at - during t
he night. Because - but we were there in the evenings 'til he come home. Oh yes, we used to go to bed, we used to - sit in the bed. And look out of the window.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Did you have to get yourself a meal then when you came in, or was there nothing to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well nothing unless of course we went errands and got these biscuits and - apples, we used to have fruit. We used to buy fruit sometimes for a change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 With the money you got from errands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 From errands, yes. Then for - Sundays used to be love
ly, we used to think, oh, lovely, Sunday father - father used to come home sometimes with - a breast of mutton. He would send me out - to get threepennyworth of - mixed vegetables. Threepennyworth mind you, and it would be enough for us - three, for us. T
here was carrots and onions and - often turnip, they'd put a turnip in - turnip in for us. And - we used to think it wonderful to have this lovely dinner. You see it was wonderful to have a lovely - Sunday dinner. Often he'd come from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Billingsgate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  and bring
 fish, we'd have fish for Sunday. They were really hard times then. And often - often - I used to go to school in the mornings, and there was one little girl, Winnie Bunting her names was, and she had lovely long fair curls. And she must - her parents mus
t
 have been well off, because she used to play the piano for us and we used to do dancing at school, and I used to watch her - she used to have - six biscuits with butter in between. I used to watch her. Oh, I'd love one of your biscuits. And if they let m
e
 turn the - turn the rope for them she'd give me a biscuit. I'll give you one of my biscuits if you turn the rope. Oh yes, I'll - I'll turn the rope. And I said, can I save one for my brother? Yes, yes. And when my - my brother used to come out from schoo
l - and I used to give him one. They were really hard times they were, but nowadays children are well - don't know how well of they are - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You remember actually being hungry quite often do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes, very often. And - when father wa
s out of work - there used to be - vans around the street - with hot soup, I don't know whether they were the mission or who, Salvation Army or who they were, but often - we used to go and they'd give us a mug - with this hot soup. Oh it was wonderful, I 
u
sed to warm my hands with it. And - when I look back I can remember all those. Of course when I was with auntie I didn't - I was never hungry. Had the best of everything. And I can remember one Christmas - being at auntie's. We went to the Albert Hall. Th
e
 fireman, at that Bishopsgate fire station were the - first - fireman to arrive at this big toy shop, a huge toyshop in London, I don't know where it was. The main shop. And they saved such a lot of property, toys and suchlike, that our men - the children
 
belonging to our men were given a - lovely party at the Albert Hall. And I can remember it was this Christmas I went. And I can remember this huge hall, and I thought of it on Saturday when we - when they had the Remembrance Service. To think I'd been the
r
e, to this party. And the Christmas tree was huge. And I came back with a drawing slate which you don't see now - it was a wooden frame and - it - wood - it had a wooden back with a piece of wood, you turn - take - turn that piece of wood and the back'd c
o
me off, and there'd be two or three pictures like that side. The different - and with a - with a - and with a slate this side. And you could trace - the different pictures. I had no end of pictures in - in that, used to like that, spent no end of that - w
i
th that, amusement with that. And then I had the skipping rope and that had bells on. You could unscrew - unscrew and put fresh bells in, if you lost a bell you could - put the bell - put another bell in. Oh I had some wonderful things, wonderful things t
his. That was the best Christmas I'd ever had when - as a child.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was it just you who went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, oh all the - all the firemen's children went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I mean in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. Oh no. 'Cos I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was only you with your aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
With Aunt Emily, yes. With them. Yes. And - oh something else I was going to tell you. No. Gone. No, we didn't used to have many toys. Only what we used to make ourselves. Used to make our own - with shoeboxes we'd make - little theatres. One thing and 
another. And the first doll I ever had was made out of a peg. Clothes peg. Grandma made me that. It was just a little head, the head part of it was made - the wooden pegs. Not like they are today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You mean like the gypsies sell in some parts, just two bits of wood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, no, not made. No, these were just the wood - the gypsies put - no, but these weren't. It was just wood and - just wood, with a round knob on the top. And this head - this knob used to be the head. And Grandma used to - put a pie
ce of wood - like that, for the arms, that'd come out for the arms, and this round piece at the top be the head. She'd draw the face and - and dress it up and it was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was your grandmother a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Oh yes. 'Cos Uncle was in the Boe
r War. And I can remember her having a - a - a piece of shell made into a - a brass - it was all made shiny, into a - a top hat. And that was my money box. She gave me that as a money box.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was an uncle who was in the Boer War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Boer War then, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that her son?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Must have been, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Was the aunt who was living with your gran when you were there, was she unmarried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Unmarried then, but she married - Uncle Arthur and went into the fire station with him you see
. That was the same one. You see I lived with grandma 'til - I suppose 'til she was married. 'Cos I can remember - auntie when she used to come home from - the - hotel, she'd bring a lot of food, we'd have a lovely feed, you know, a lovely meal. And - she
 
used to make all her own clothes and make my clothes too. And - and she used to make those mutton - leg o'mutton sleeves. I remember her - her fitting this on this model that they used to have, and - and she used to let me put those big - stiffeners in th
e
 neck, used to wear the high necks didn't they then. And often, I remember once - I took them all out, she was going to a party - a dance or something, and I took all these - things out, oh I got a good hiding for that. And - another thing I - when I was 
w
ith auntie, she used to go up to - Hampstead Heath do you remember Hampstead Heath, you know Hampstead Heath? Well that was another aunt of mine, Aunt Mary Ann, they used to - their name was Cox. And they used to own the roundabout and swings on Hampstead
 
Heath, and this aunt I lived with used to go and help them at holiday times. Easter - August - Whitsun. Three times. And she used to take me with her and - I could go on anything, the roundabout, swings and anything and this aunt I remember - she used to 
h
ave a caravan up - up on - up on - above ground, and then you'd go down some steps, and there was like an underneath - underground flat. And there'd be storerooms - underneath - where she used to live. And - I remember going into this caravan that was on 
-
 above ground. And - I should - I was not allowed really to go in there but I did go in there, and - they were counting out the money. And you know these - the boxes - the tin boxes the soldiers had to put their - ammunition in? There was two of those. An
d
 they were all full of sovereigns. I often think of that - all that money. I think to myself, I wonder what they did with all that money. And she wanted me to stay with her. Then. Yes. But I wouldn't, I wouldn't, no, I wanted to stay with Aunt Emily. I co
u
ld have been well off I reckon if I'd have stayed with her. And - the only thing that I regretted, I - I'm very fond of music. And I always wanted to know how to play the piano. Always, that's been - right - even now. If I won a lot of money - that's what
 I'd do, buy a piano, and get someone to - to teach me, as old as I am. I love music. That's why I bought that - organ. Mind you I only just play by ear now but - I can sit and watch anybody play the - piano, for hours. I love music. Any music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Could you have learnt if you'd gone there do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes, if I'd have stayed with her. I could have had a piano and - she said, see what you've missed, because I went to see her when - I was about eighteen. Just before the war - the 1918 war finishe
d. And she said - she'd got a piano then. She said, see what you missed, if you'd have stayed with me you could have played like that. She had daughters of her own then. She said, see what you've missed. And of course I started crying. Naturally. But stil
l, never mind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did Aunt Emily have a piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you didn't learn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. I didn't. The only two - when her children arrived. They did. Oh I - often regret - oh if only I - I could have played. Even now I love to watch. I think 
if you can sit down and play - that'd be the - one wish of my life. To know how to play, sit down and play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your grandmother have a piano in her home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, oh no. No, nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did any of your homes have any other musical instruments at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well Aunt Lucy, she had a piano, and she had two daughters, my cousins, and she put them to music. And often when I - used to go there - I didn't used to stay with her. But when I used to go and see her - I used to love to get into the 
front room and play the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Which one was Aunt Lucy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
My real auntie. My mother's sister. The one that was wheel - wheelwright, that lived opposite the - Balaam Street baths. That one there. Oh - I loved to feel the keys. The feel of the keys, under my hands. I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 do now}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 . It's silly really, but there - funny. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever go to concerts or hear any music played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When I was with Aunt Emily I did. She took me to the theatre once. And - I don't know what play it was but I was watchin
g the orchestra. I was watching the orchestra. She said, what are you looking down there for? I said, they're playing the piano down there. I don't know what the - what the play was about but I remember the orchestra.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was your father musical, do you think he had an interest in music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I couldn't tell you, I don't know. No, mother died very - young, she was only about - thirty-nine I think she was and she had eight children. Yes. One after the other you see and that's what - killed her I think
. And they - I can remember my auntie saying, if only you'd have been - Dolly we could have spared her better than we could mother, 'cos Dolly was a cripple.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was she the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, she was next to me, she was only thirteen years - thirteen m
onths - older than I, I was the youngest girl, you see. And I think mother - often think now that could have been me. And I remember when she - father couldn't - finish paying for her, she - he used to play - pay for her when she was in - Whipps Cross. An
d
 she was sent home, and I remember her being in a long - long box, strapped in this box, with two legs, her legs were strapped and her body was strapped, and we used to stand her up against the wall us children, and gradually - used to undo one strap and 
w
e'd get one leg and we'd work it. And we'd work it 'til she - got on her knees and she used - to crawl on a chair - round the table, and she gradually got so she walked. She could walk, holding onto things. And - and by the time she left - she was taken a
way again she could walk. Mind you, she was deformed. Mind it was the back that was gone, T.B. in the back. But she could walk. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When she came from Whipps Cross do you think she'd been kept mainly lying down while she was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Becau
se I remember father taking me on the tram to see her. And I was awfully ill - on the tram. They used to say you see so. And I was always a bad traveller then, as a child, and - but I can remember seeing her in this - and do you know I had the thought she
 
was in the coffin, in a coffin. To me as a child it did. I'd seen mother's coffin, and seeing her like that. I used - I said to father, is she in a coffin? I said, but she's talking. I said, she's talking. And of course father was - out of work I suppose 
and she had to come home again. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No National Health Service then of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No - no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did Dolly manage to do anything to help in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, she couldn't. She couldn't. No. When we got her walking, as I tell you, th
e cripple carriage used to come for her. And I used to help her - I used to have to - one of us had to be with her because if she fell down she couldn't get up again you see. And I remember fighting with a boy that - hit her. Whether he'd hit her or not, 
b
ut anyway she was knocked down by him, and I remember fighting this boy. Because he hit my sister. But anyway, this - this - carriage used to take them to - Nelson Square, to a big house there. 'Cos I went with her one day. And they used to teach them to 
do - sewing, embroidery and suchlike. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Hoping that they could earn their living and be self-supporting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes. Yes. Take a trade you see, take on a trade. But she - she - her - hers was sewing. It used to take her a long while bu
t she managed it. But - but of course she was taken away again you see because - I suppose it wasn't fit for her to be with us, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Because of the T.B?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did any other rest of you contract it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well no - when I was twe
lve - I was twelve, that'd be 19 - 1913, that's right, I was - my two eldest sisters were at the orphanage then in Leicester. And they went out to service and there was a vacancy. And Aunt Lucy, the one that lived at Balaam Street opposite the baths, she 
got me - into - one of their places, you see, and that was a very strict church - orphanage, there were only twenty-five children. Never see a ragged child, or a child without shoes like I used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You used to see that often did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You say a vacancy became available at the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes? At Leicester that was. And I went to this orphanage, and then - that was very strict. We had navy blue and white uniform. And for breakfast - in the wintertime we just had - a little porri
dge and some bread and dripping and a cup of tea. That was breakfast. And for dinner - well used to have - cold meat Mondays. And mince Tuesday, and - never had any treats. The best - the best treat we had was - was the school, used to be the Wiggeston Gi
r
ls School, that was the High School for Girls, and each girl was given a child's name from the orphanage, and that girl made up a parcel, a Christmas parcel. There'd be a toy, there'd be something useful like a - a shoe - cleaning outfit or writing pad, a
nd then a game. And we used to watch for that hamper to come Christmas. We'd say, here the hampers come. And we used to think wonderful, that was our - that was our Christmas treat that was. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you there at that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh I was - four years. Yes. 'Til I was sixteen. Sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You went when you were about twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. Yes. And I had one year during the war years. I can remember - being in church one Sunday evening and all the lights went out and we had to come ho
me. And the - another evening, I didn't go to Sunday - didn't go to church that evening, I don't know why but I didn't, and I used to have to look after the little ones, and - the policeman knocked on the door and we were all lined up outside. No, we'd go
n
e to bed, that's right, we'd gone to bed. It was eight o'clock. And we were all taken downstairs and - we picked up our little treasures that we thought were our treasures, and stood outside the door. And the - the policeman would say and the Matron would
 say - he'd say to the Matron, I'll - I'll tell you when it's safe to take them in. And next to - because next door to - the orphanage was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 munitions}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  factory, so I suppose they took us out to be on the safe side. If anything was dropped. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there much bombing then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, not in Leicester, we didn't used to get the bombs there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there any zeppelins there or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh there was some zeppelins went over but we were lucky, they went over. They didn't do any damage, n
ot in Leicester. And - when it was all quiet he used to say, you can get them back again now. But it was a very strict Church of England - orphanage, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All girls, oh no, no boys. No, we weren't allowed to speak to any boys. No. Oh
 no, my word, if we spoke to - seen talking to anybody or any stranger - we were reported, we were reported and we'd have - bread for tea and a cup of tea and go straight to bed after - out of school. And we'd have that for a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just for teatime, not the other meals as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Oh no, no, we'd have our breakfast and meal - and midday meal but tea, we just had dry bread, cup of tea and straight to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That would be quite early I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Straight from school. Just after tea. About five o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just dry bread would it be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Dry bread, yes, and a cup of tea. That was our punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever get any other punishment there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they ever hit the children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well I remember once, I
 was only in the middle class there - middle girls, there was the children - the younger ones, and I was in the middle section then, being twelve year old, and - the big girls had the big room to themselves. There was seven in there. And - at church, they
 used to look at the choirboys, naturally, we were - we were taught - to sing the - psalms, and the hymns, exactly as the choir sang them, because we were next to the organ and we had the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 proper Psalters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 , you see, and we had to know - know the psalms for ea
ch day. And sometimes the Matron used to say when we were having prayers, you two sing the next verse. And if we made a mistake and didn't do stops where there should be - stop. And used to have to - start again. And - we'd have to know what }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 psalms}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  were fo
r the day, what Saints day it was, all the chapters of the Bible. I can tell you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8995913\charrsid675430 no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 w, mind you, but I get so far and - I'm finished. And - and we used to have to go church in the morning. Say eleven o'clock, or those that were confirmed would have to go ei
ther six, seven or eight o'clock service, then you'd go at eleven, Matins. You'd go to Sunday school in the afternoon. And-then again in the evening at half past six. And then during Lent we'd go twice a week up to any church, I remember walking right up 
t
o Weston Park which is two mile - a good two mile, for a Lenten service, this is during the week. And - oh we got a real religious teaching there. Yes, that's where I learnt - you know, took to religion there. Yes. And - I was confirmed in fact from there
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were all the girls confirmed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes, you were bound to be confirmed, that was the law.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But did you want to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, you were bound to do. That was the law then. You were - you were confirmed and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 After that did you take Communion every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, not every Sunday. We did it at least once a - once a month. We could go every week if we wanted to. But I didn't stay all the service, it was too long a service, it was a - sometimes it'd be a long - almost like Mas
s. It'd be a long service, High Church you see, and I couldn't stand it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you had nothing to eat beforehand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Even those who weren't taking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Communion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  had nothing to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Nothing to eat. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have to walk to the church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Even in winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, in the winter. And - what else was I going to say? I was going to say something else just now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Something about the church services, or food or punishments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh, the punishments -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
You were telling me about how you had to start again if you got anything wrong in the psalms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we learnt - we learnt four - four songs and a carol for the Christmas. And the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 committee'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  come down - belonging to the orphanage, and - they
'd - we'd have to sit - he in our best - uniform. We used to have three dresses. One for work, one for school, and one for Sundays. And we'd all be in our - in our Sunday best and then the committee'd be there in this big hall and - they'd read out the na
m
es, so and so, first prize for best - good behaviour, we didn't know it, but - the Matron used to take notes of who was good and who was bad and who was corrected and how many times you were punished and suchlike. Well one year I was - I came top. I didn'
t
 know, I didn't know that. And - we all sat down, and no - stood there and sang our songs, and then the prize giving and gifts were given out, from the Wiggeston Girls School. My name was read out. Me? No, it's not me. It is you. And of course we didn't k
n
ow the - the - 'cos the Matron used to put names - marks down against our names you see unknown to us. And - oh I was telling you, the - the big girls, in church - used to look at the choirboys. And - that's it - and - I was in the middle - middle bedroom
 
then, and it was a stone floor mind you, this bedroom, stone floor. And - there was such a - we were all called down into the Matron's sitting room. That's in - the middle room. And - she said, do you - have you anything to do with this - I said, what - w
h
at do you mean, I said, what are you talking about? Have you been taking letters to school? It seems the big girls had had been giving some of the girls in my - my section, letters to take to the choirboys at school, because some of the choirboys were in 
o
ur class at school you see, unbeknown. And - one evening - the under matron, Miss Wilcock, she was going out and one - the girls were at the front of the hall - front of the orphanage their bedrooms was at the front. And they were letting these - letters 
d
own, on string, to the choirboys. They were hiding round the corner. And when they saw this - giving these letters you see. That's how they were passed. And there was four girls in my section that were doing this at school, some were taking them to school
 
and giving them to the boys you see. But I didn't know anything about this. 'Til - I don't - I - we were all called down, us - us six of us in this - middle bedroom. Have you - do you know anything about - no, no, I hadn't - of course I didn't know anythi
n
g. Luckily I got away with that, there was nothing - I didn't - I wasn't punished for that. But the big girls were punished. They had to come into a - the little girls bedrooms and us - the little ones as we called them, and - and the middle ones, went in
to the big room. Oh it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 to be in the big room. That was their punishment. And when we went to church, the big ones - girls naturally would sit in the front. But after that, they were - had to sit at the back. And they used to have bread teas f
or a long long while they had bread teas for that. Yes, one girl was expelled. Yes. Mary Kershaw, now where did she come from, somewhere near - somewhere down South anyway. She was - I said, well where is she? Oh and Rosina. I said, where's Rosina, 'cos t
h
ey were big girls. Well when you left school, the - for - in the orphanage, you left school at fourteen then, and you went into the laundry, in the wash house. And you wore clogs, and rubber aprons and you were all - stood at these wash tubs, and you were
 
washing all day long and dollying. Dollying tubs, not - the machines. There was no - they were dolly tubs. We used to take in washing - to keep the orphanage going you see. And - two days solid washing, nothing else but washing and dollying and pegging ou
t
 clothes, for two days, and the place used to get full of steam, there was two big coppers. One on each side of the place. And the - heated by fire. Coal. And suchlike. One girl'd be stoker as we called her. She'd have to keep these fires going to keep th
e
 things boiling, and there was hampers and hampers of washing. And I know when I first left school - there was - hundred and fifty surplices from churches, different churches we used to - wash. Blankets - sheets, curtains, table linen. Beautiful table lin
e
n, Irish - Irish linen. And that was two days solid washing. And then the rest of the week - Wednesday, Thursday and Friday was up in the laundry. And you'd - have all this ironing to do. There was babies washing, baby's clothes. And there was big hampers
 
- as big as that table, full of nothing else but - vests and pyjamas - vests, pants and socks, and they all had to be brushed - ironed and folded properly. Brushed. Yes. The socks were brushed. Brushed, yes. The pile - the pile they used to call it. The s
ocks used to have to be brushed. Both sides, and then folded properly and ironed and each one put in their proper - place, and when you first went into the laundry you started on the girls clothes, the - the orphanage }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 children's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 ' clothes. Started on the apr
ons, children used to wear pinafores and girls when you leave - left school, well you went into aprons. And - you started on that and handkerchiefs, and then you went - moved up to higher on the table and you did - the maids' things that come with the lau
n
dry. The maids' things from houses like the big houses. You did the maids things. And then you went on to surplices - then the table clothes, and then the baby linen and the head one, the - Miss Woolcock, she used to do the collars - and the cuffs. And so
m
e of the pillowcases, the baby's pillowcases for the prams and suchlike, it had - a frill to iron - and crimp, do you now how - crimping? And then - there'd be - one round of it would be crimped, and then the - on the other side, the - on the - next to it
 
there'd be a lace frill and that'd have to be go offered. Yes. Oh yes, special iron for crimping and go offering as well. And the collars used to have a different iron. A little iron like - quite - so big, and it was round. Bottom surface was round so as 
t
o get the collars - make the collars round. And they were fitted into a - a - what did they call it - a brass band, so as to keep them round, and polished. But - that - the head one used to do that, we were not allowed to do that. But surplices, oh dear. 
A
nd there was alter clothes. Purificators that they wiped the chalices with. They had to be perfect. One little smudge - and she'd throw it back into the - into a bowl of water and you had to do it all over again. And blouses. Blouses. And the - in those d
ays the ladies used-to wear - what they called pique skirts for tennis. And the - and men white flannels. And only the - high girls used to do that, you know, the ones that were - experienced girls used to do that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that more like dry cleaning to do the flannels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, ironing. Washed and ironing. Oh yes, and pressed. And I remember once when I was on the - linen table. There'd be - four girls - two or three girls that side. And two or three girls that side. We used to have long - huge linen she
ets. And - we'd iron each way and - and if your irons met - clicked it would cut the - cut the - whichever you were doing, sheets or tablecloths. And I can remember doing that once. Only a little tiny - cut. But oh dear, dear, dear, I was punished for tha
t. Two of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did they do to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just have dry bread for tea. And go to bed with the little ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 For a whole week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. And upstairs - once you got upstairs there was not a word spoken. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not on any occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. The monitor - one girl used to - be chosen monitor, for the year, I was chosen once - for monitor. And - you have to report anybody that was - even - motioning - miming, that wanted anything. And I can remember in the wintertime we used to have to st
rip, get down to our nightdresses, vests off, we used to tie our nightdresses round with our - selves, and we'd wash in cold water. And we often used to break the ice, on the buckets of water underneath the - the - the washing - the - dressing table, the 
- the wash stands rather, enamel bowls, and we'd have to break the ice in winter when it was very cold, to wash with. Always wash in cold water, winter and summer. I used to dread it. Yes. I used to lay in bed and shiver 'til I went to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you ever able to have a warm bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, we had to be bathed every night - every - every week. Once a week. Oh yes. But - that - we used to have to carry the water up from the bath - from the wash house. There was four big girls - used to carry four bu
ckets of hot water to the bathroom, right through the laundry, right up there at the end of the place. Right at the end, the coldest part of the place. And there used to be four girls to each bath - of water. Four girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So the last one wouldn't be very nice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we used to have - four girls to each bath of water. So every four - fourth girl there'd be a fresh lot of water. See what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Three girls had to share the water you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes. And - you see, and then there was - they'
d say, another lot of water, you go - you go, you go, and each take a bucket of hot water up. Mind you not the little ones. And I remember when - the war started, the 1914 war started, and the big girls who all had - went out to service. Left us little on
e
s as we used to call it then, we were little then, and we couldn't carry on the laundry. We weren't big enough to do it. You see, it was too much. And us little ones used to come in at five and six year old then. And they were too - in fact we used to hav
e the girls sitting room, that was a stone floor, but we had - used to have a bath in front of a - a stove - like the Army - stoves the Army used to - used to have, they still have in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 barracks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 . The round ones with the - pipes going through the wall. The
n we'd have the - bath, little bath in - in front of that to bath the little ones. So you can tell - so of course the laundry went down and - and I remember when I left they - the Matorn collapsed and died and the - the home went then. That was after I le
ft, because - soon after I left, because - it was - it joined onto the Technical school. The Leicester Technical school, High School, and they took over that - plot of land and joined it onto their - their - the school, the Technical - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Technical}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  college you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So all the girls had to leave then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
The big ones left and - just left us little ones so of course they - couldn't carry on. So gradually the little ones were sent to different homes and - then it was disbanded, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How many adults were in charge there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was only two, the Matron and the Under Matron.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What were they like as people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh the Matron was sweet. Really nice. She was a - a Catholic, she come from Canterbury. She really was nice. And - I can remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that Anglican Catholic or Roman Catholic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, she was Roman Catholic. Roman Catholic because she used to go to Canterbury Cathedral. And her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 niece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  was - organist there. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But really it was Church of England?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. The orphana
ge itself was Church of England. And - she was really sweet, but the - the Under Matron, she was a very strict, at least I used to think she was because if you - left a little dry patch in - on a - on the - on your ironing, she'd throw it back into the wa
t
er and you had to do it all over - which I thought was very cruel. But anyway - I suppose it was good teaching. But each girl had to go out into service - from there. We were not allowed to do - say if you wanted to - say you were musical or anything like
 that, you weren't given music lessons or anything like that, you'd got to go into domestic service, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you get any money in the laundry for what you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, no, we never got any money. Oh no, the only money I used to get was - my t
wo sisters, as I told you, they were - they would be gone out to service in front of me, they used to come and see me on their half days, and they'd leave - give me some pennies, you see. But - at - between - Lent to Easter, we'd have no sweets at all. An
d what money that we would have spent on sweets - had to go into the church box, what they called the church - church box.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was your Lenten sacrifice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes. Church finance. And we - and in the winter we used - we - we'd wear - bl
ack straw hats. And in the summer we'd wear white straw hats. Yes. Yes. And clogs to - in the wash house. Clogs. I can remember going to this cupboard where they kept all the clogs, and there used to be huge black beetles. Oh. Oh I used to pick them up an
d throw them on the floor to see if there was any beetles in them. Before I put them on. Dear oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your father ever come and visit you while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. No. No, I don't know what became of him, he was always in lodgings after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you lose track of him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. Until I was about eighteen. And then I went to see him, in - where was he now - at Plaistow. 'Cos I went to Aunt Lucy's, to see her to have a holiday when I was eighteen, and I went to see my fa
ther. He was in rooms then. And - I knocked on the door, and he was sitting in - a chair, similar to that, and he clutched the arms of the chair and he said, oh, you're your mother come back again. And he went as white as a sheet. And I never would see hi
m again, it upset me so to see him upset. I wouldn't go to see him again. Silly really but - there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You must have looked very like your mother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
I was more like mother then, very much like mother. Oh and another thing I must tell you. I reme
mber the Lord Mayor's shows in London. I was only little then, because I remember being on the Embankment and I couldn't see, I could hear them, and see the horses hooves. And I said, I can't see. And - I don't know what man it was but he picked me up and
 put me on his shoulder, and I saw everything beautifully. There was the carriages and the - the - floats, the - decorated floats and the - sailors and firemen, everything. And guns. Beautiful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was a real treat was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh it was lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you see that every year or just once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No - I only saw it once. Yes. And - then we had - I believe it was a Coronation. My second - Christian name was Alexandra. And I wonder if it was Queen Alexandra's Coronation, because I remember having meda
ls - and a mug. Every child had one. And I have an idea that was - for that Coronation. But what became of them I don't know. But - and then - then when I was with Aunt Emily - I don't know whether you remember hearing of Petticoat Lane. Do they still hav
e
 it? Well I was always forbidden to go down there, when I was with auntie because she said, you'll get - you'll get taken away if you do. Anyway I was allowed to go down with her. And it was a wonderful treat to see all these men - that had carpets on the
i
r backs and - oh they'd be talking all - foreign languages. It used to amuse me to hear them talking. But you - you know - they - used to say - you can have your watch one end of the market and you get to the bottom and you - it was missing, somebody had 
taken it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did she buy things there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, she used to buy - lots of things there. And the stalls weren't lit - by lamps, they were flares. Yes, you - you've seen pictures in olden days - of the soldiers - Roman soldiers with flares. Well those 
sort of - all - gasoline - no, not gasoline, what would it be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you think it would have been oil?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Naptha or some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
such thing as that. Used to flare anyway and used to think - if only the - if these stalls caught alight what would he do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So there was a lot of interesting things to see and a lot of variety in a way?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. And I can remember another thing, when I used to go - from Aunt Emily's - when I - when she used to send me over to see grandma to take these things to grandma 
- when I got over to Blackfriars Bridge, there was a - a telephone box sort of thing. There'd be - a sort of thing like the telephone but of course it wouldn't be a telephone box, but it'd be a - a case like that, and there was always a diver - a diver's 
uniform in that box. And I used to think - oh there's my diver. I'm nearly there. Used to think, well nearly there. And I can see that now. I wonder if it - often wonder if it's still there. Yes. But oh -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You said you got twelve pounds a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Twelve pound a year. And I was paid - one pound a month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you had the incident with the bathroom who was it that reprimanded you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh that's the parlourmaid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was she over you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes, and - it was her that told me what 
to do you see - in the mornings I used to work with the cook 'til about eleven o'clock. But then after that I was the parlourmaids - helper you see. And - of course being wartime we were - rationed. Food was rationed. Miss Ellis used to have a - lady comp
a
nion. And it was her duty to come and - and - allow - allot all the - provisions to us. There was tea, sugar - margarine, not butter, margarine. What else was it she - oh and cheese. All things. You see, and I didn't take sugar and I didn't like cheese th
ose days. So of course I used to take them to my sister that was married. Then. You see? Oh and Miss Ellis always wanted to know what you did on your days out. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How would she ask you, would she summon you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She'd say, well where did you - o
h yes, in the - Monday morning - where did you go yesterday when you were out? Did you go to church? I said, yes, I did, I went to this - with Jessie. So she said to me, what did they - what was the sermon? Often she'd ask me what the text was of the serm
on. Sometimes I would remember and sometimes not. But - you had to make - had to make sure that you were going to church. And then - the following Sunday, the following fortnight rather when it was my Sunday off - I'd go to my sister's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You'd get a whole day once a fortnight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, not a whole day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You mean still that six to eight period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just - that's right, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long did it take you to get to your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh it took me about - twenty minutes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So you didn't have very long with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No, no, oh no. And - I can remember the war finishing, because it was my evening off, I believe it was on a Tuesday when it finished. And I wouldn't go because there was fires and people were absolutely going mad. It wa
s terrible, the - they were pulling everything down, the wire - the wooden fences and burning them, making }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 bonfires}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  everywhere. And there was terrific noise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was in Leicester was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh that was in Leicester, yes. From there I went - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was she an elderly lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, she was - seventy. Seventy then. And - the way she used to dress, she used to have the crinoline dresses on and her hair - snow white hair, and she'd have it done up in a - knob at the top. Then she'd have
 two roses in her hair in the summer when she used to entertain the - wounded soldiers. The wounded soldiers used to have a - a blue uniform like this, that come from the hospital, and she'd have them in the garden for - afternoon tea and suchlike. And of
 course when - the parlourmaid was out it was my duty to wait on them. I used to be terrified. I wouldn't now mind you but I was - I hadn't got a young man then and - was terrified - every - awfully nervous. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 If you had had a young man would she h
ave allowed you to go out with him do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I suppose so. She'd have asked me of course. I should have to ask her permission. Because when my brother came home on leave - the cook - told me, there's a - young man asking for you, he says he'
s your brother. So of course I told Jessie the house - the parlourmaid and - I said, I'd like to go out with him. Well, she said, you'd better go up and ask the mistress then. So of course you'd go to go upstairs and - knock on the mistress' door and say,
 may I come in? She said, what is it? And you'd tell her. And - she let me go out with him. But I'd got to be home at a certain - at - now what was the time - nine o'clock. Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You got an extension?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, nine o'clock. Be home a
t nine o'clock. She asked to see him of course. She surprised me very much. Oh yes. She was in - came down into the drawing room. She was resting. And - I took him into the drawing room and she - asked me where he come from and where he'd been. He was in 
t
he North Irish Horse then, and - of course I went out with him. It was very nice. But - when I was out with him he says, you're not stopping there, he says. He says, you're go silly if you stop there with those two elderly people to live with all the whil
e. Because I used to have to share a bedroom with Jessie the parlourmaid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How old was Jessie then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh well she was turned - over fifty. And the other one was sixty - odd. So I was only just like sixteen between the two. You see. And I used to sh
are a bedroom with - Jessie. And why I left there - I'll tell you the truth why I did leave there. Jessie had a letter one morning, and she used to - letters were on the breakfast table in the kitchen naturally. And - she went - used to go upstairs and re
a
d her letters in the bedroom. Which I never used to do, if I had a letter, which wasn't very often, but I did, I'd open it straight away to see who it was from. But I never took any notice, well then - one day she accused me of going to her - we had one c
h
est of drawers between us, and we had one little drawer each and the other three between us. And she accused me of going - going to this drawer and reading a letter. I said, I don't read your letter. I said, they're no use to me. I said, your letters don'
t
 interest me. Something she said, and I said, no I don't remember. She said, oh you read my letters. I said, I don't. That's a thing I would never do, read any body elses' letter, 'cos they're of no interest to me, not at her age. But anyway I said - don'
t
 you believe me? She said, no. Well, I said, well I'm going to see the mistress then. Because, I said, I came here with a clean character and I'm going away with a clean character. So I went to the mistress. She says, what is it? So I said, I've been accu
s
ed of reading Jessie's letters, which I - honestly did not do. So I said, do you believe me? She said, oh that's not - not my prerogative, she said, you - settle your own quarrels. I said, oh no. I said, I'm not stopping here if I can't be believed. Oh no
, I said, I've always had a clean character, I said, I came here with a clean character and I want a clean one going home - going away. And then I left. She wouldn't believe me. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What sort of a character did she give you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh she gave me a 
very good character because when I left - the day I left - she wanted the charriage and - it was hansome cab then, and saw my - boxes onto the carriage, paid for the carriage to take me to my sister. She couldn't have been nicer. But she would not take - 
the responsibility of sorting that quarrel out, and seeing fair play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That seems out of character from what you've told me about her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It wasn't right. Oh. More thought, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you think she was frightened of the parlourmaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well I th
ink so because she'd been there so long you see, and she knew her ways. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I suppose she felt it was either her or you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. And she'd take her word before - and me being so young I suppose she thought - well I must have done you see. Well I mean, what - what was her letter to me at that age?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What was it about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I don't know. I couldn't tell you what was in the letter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You never found out what it was all about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It must have been something she wanted to hide did you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. I used to think all sorts of things. I thought, well if - if they don't believe me what's the good of me stopping here, if they can't trust me, because I've got to share a bedroom with her you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So you just had this one room,
 did you have separate beds or did you have to share a bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It had two beds - oh no, our own beds. Big beds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And just the one chest of drawers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have a cupboard to hang up your things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. We had that. 
But it used to amuse me the way she was dressed. She used to dress. She - saw me watching her one day, she said, what are you looking at, she said, you go to sleep. And - she - she had long chemise on, they used to call them chemises then, they were made 
o
f linen. And then she put her corsets on - oh ever so stiff they were. Of course I only had a - a liberty bodice on sort of affair. But she had these stiff - and - bones down the front, and then she'd have long bloomers on. On - on top of this - these cor
s
ets, long - right down to her ankles with lace at the edges. Yes. I said, what do you wear those long things for? She says, it's nothing to do with you. I was awfully rude I suppose, but still the - curious. And then she'd wear another - long petticoat on
 top of that, two petticoats she used to wear, and then her frock. Oh I thought to myself, oh, fancy having all that lot on. Of course now I'm cold now but still - I was only young then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And her dress was long was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Used to swish o
n the floor. Miss Ellis expected me to wear the same you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When she told you Jessie must put an addition to your dress to make it longer did Jessie do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, undid the - undid the hem, and of course when I got to my sister's she says,
 you're not going about like that, she said, and she undid it and did it up again. And of course Miss Ellis saw it the next day I went out you see. Oh yes, without thinking you know I - I put it on and naturally went out and she had - must have been looki
ng out of the bedroom window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did she do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh I had to take it up again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did Jessie do it again then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, my sister did. Jessie wouldn't do it, she said, I've done it once, I'm not doing it again for you. And she said, well, s
he said - it was her too, she says, oh you mustn't stop there, she said, you can't go on like that, you're only a youngster yet. She expects you to be the same as them. 'Cos she had - but in that room - we used to - and we used to think it was wonderful -
 the - the wonderful - oh it must have been - thousands of pounds worth of - ornaments and silver in that drawing room. And every evening - it was the parlourmaid's duty to put this - silver - the best silver, onto a tray - on a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 baize}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  green tray, and take i
t up to the mistress' bedroom every night. Even that in the sideboard. The little - salt - condiment sets, all that had to go up on - on this - two trays in fact, two trays upstairs into the bedroom, every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Why was that, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 In ca
se of burglary. She was so afraid someone - was going to - even - and yet - yet the dining - the - panty - the cupboards were full of silver. The silver tureens and the silver - dishes, vegetable dishes with the covers on. And - what else - the - cake - s
t
ands, silver cake stands, and the tea - teapot sets, everything. All in there, there was no end of them in there, but - of course - that was always double locked. The doors were - locked top and bottom. And - and key as well. Jessie used to have the bunch
 of keys on a - in her pocket. Hip pocket. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But the stuff that couldn't be locked up had to be taken up to her bedroom?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Every night. Yes. Up to the mistress' bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did she have family prayers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, she didn't. No, she d
idn't but - another situation I had - was - now she wasn't a Quakeress, she was a - chapel person. Miss - Mrs Tyler. She was married. She was very nice. And they used to have daily prayers - always. There was only me there too. I was the - the one general
 maid there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Miss Ellis had a groom you said who left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He left, and - when I went there was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 gardener}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 and a houseboy. And then Jessie and - Fanny, the cook. Peculiar name. But - and Miss Ellis would - as I told, you, always had this water filte
red and - she'd have a little glass - dish on her - tray that we took up for breakfast. Then she'd - and I used - my job to - used the butter pats and make little tiny fancy - patterns of butter. Six in this little glass - glass dish, and put a tiny bit o
f - parsley in, for decoration - every morning regular. It - she was - don't matter - if she was on her own or whatever she had for breakfast that - butter dish was got to be just so. Whether she used the butter or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What else did she have for breakfast, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Let me see. Egg mostly. And - or grapefruit. Toast and marmalade. Oh yes, toast and marmalade every morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did she always have it in her room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 In the wintertime. Yes. Well - I should think every - yes, it was every
 time, every - every morning because - she didn't used to get up 'til about dinnertime. Lunch. Midday you see - in the summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Then she'd come down would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, in the afternoon. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What time did they have lunch there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I
 think usually one o'clock, unless there were visitors. All depends who - if there was visitors we'd have it early or later whichever they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What sort of things would she have at lunchtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She'd have soup every day in winter. Not always in the 
summer. But - when I was there helping Jessie, always. There'd be fish. She'd have - fish if she was on her own. In midday. And - just a sweet. And then she'd have a full course in the evening you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How many courses did she have in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
In the evening - when she was on her own, she used to have six. When she was downstairs. But up in her bedroom she'd have two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She sometimes even had her evening meal in her bedroom?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. In the bedroom in the wintertime. Yes. She sort of
 lived in her bedroom all the winter. And of course she had this - companion with her all the while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was she sort of separate from the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes. She never - didn't interfere with us at all. Only gave us our rations out when the rations - came along. And she had her own room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What was her name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Miss Sneath. Miss Sneath, she was always - maiden lady of course. But - she was very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did you call the cook there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Fanny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She wasn't called Mrs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. No. No. And Miss Sneath, the companion, I would call her Miss Sneath. And Miss Ellis used to go to - Harrogate once a year, she used to stay with a month - a month with Lord and Lady Reckitt. The Reckitts Blue people if you remember. She stay
ed always - or was it the mustard people. No - Reckitts Blue that's right. Because she had - used to take the - waters. The spa waters. And she was there a month and of course we used to have to spring clean the house through. And there was carpet beating
 on the lawn and suchlike and these wooden carpet beaters we used to have then, and I know - know one afternoon we were clean - we were cleaning out the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 box room}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  as we called it. A little room half this size. And - I said, what are all these trunks? And it was absolutely full of trunks - and cases, suitcases, and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 whickers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 baskets. Because there was not many suitcases those days, it was all wicker baskets. And - all these huge trunks. And - I opened one one day, and there was these little - Quaker bonnets, th
e crinoline frocks - of course - oh I was awful I suppose but I went and put this bonnet on once. Jessie went downstairs for something or other, I don't know what it was, but anyway - don't I look nice? Oh dear, she did tell me off. Oh dear, she said, wha
t would Miss Ellis say if you - if she saw you? Put that away. She wouldn't touch a thing. I said, I'm only trying it on to see what I look like. I suppose I was - young like. Naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did Quakers were different sort of clothes at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 We
ll she did, she used to wear - crinoline and in the - from the hall was this beautiful white staircase. Oak }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 panelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
