s who were interested in the orphanage though weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ah, she was on the committee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you never met them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No - oh yes, I did meet the ladies. Yes. Yes, there was Miss Emrod and there was Miss Gelly, and Miss Ellis of course. Mrs B
lunt. Mrs Cora. Oh there was about a dozen on the committee, but of course the orphanage was run through them. They - it was voluntary for them, and it was also kept up by the laundry work that was done by the - the older girls you see. Yes, if it wasn't 
f
or them the - that's why the - the - place - orphanage was - disbanded because you see the big girls - big girls, when the war broke out, some went on the land - those that were old enough. And of course the little ones - we could not do it, we were at sc
hool you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So there was no revenue coming in from the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, you see gradually it went down and down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever meet Miss Ellis and these other ladies while you were there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, at the orphanage, yes, there used to be a
 - committee meeting once a month. And any girl that was - anything wrong or - or done anything wrong or - or they wanted to know anything about - the girl. I remember they - in the orphanage when I - I think I mentioned it to you, I was made monitor one 
year. I'd just left school then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You had to stop the girls from talking upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. And - the bell rang and this - we were in the laundry this day - and they said, Helen, used to call me Helen there because there was another Nelliw, y
ou see, so I was called Helen. And - you're wanted in the committee room. I thought, what have I done wrong now? So I had to put a - when you leave school, instead of wearing pinafores you wore - wore white aprons. So of course I had to put a clean apron 
o
n and do my hair. And - put my best ribbon on. Oh no, when we left school we had - had to do our hair up in a bun, that's right, we had to do our hair up in a bun. Anyway I went up to the committee room, knocked on the door, come in. And they said, now we
'
ve had a very good report - from Matron about you. You've been trustworthy, you've worked very hard for the - for the last year and you're one of the elder ones, I was the third eldest then - we - we've decided to make you monitor for the year. Will you o
b
ey these rules? And of course they put out the rules what I was to keep - silence in the bedroom, take charge when - Matron or other under Matron was out of the room, and - as soon as the bell went in the morning, Matron rang her bell at half past six, I 
w
as to get up, make tea, and take tea to Matron and the Under Matron, and hot water. And then see to the girls all did their work. Even the children that went to school, that's - the children that went to school always had their work to do before breakfast
.
 The youngest was allowed to - she had to - dust down the bedroom - the stairs leading to the bedroom. The next youngest was - duster girl, she had to dust all the chairs in the girls sitting room. And - we each had our own jobs to do. And before I left s
c
hool I remember - there was there of us. We had to do the mangling. - Mangling in those days, and the girls washing. I suppose we were chattering, not taking - a look at what we were doing, and my finger went through the mangle. With the clothes, I was - 
getting a - a - the corners, and naturally it want up. I remember that. I was off - off school for - oh - about three weeks - but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you go to hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No, there was no hospital then, we went to the doctor, I passed out several times and I remember them taking me to the doctor. And - I was off - I had my arm in a sling. And - I used to do things left handed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You are left handed are you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You had to do things left handed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Then. Yes. But every girl had 
a job to do. Now - on a Sunday morning - the Matron'd say, stand, and we'd all stand at the table from breakfast, we'd stand up. Wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8995913\charrsid675430 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  is bedroom girl this week? We each used to take it in rotation. One week you'd be bedroom girl, another one sitting room gi
rl. Another - housemaid. Laundrymaid. Wash girl, the wash room, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 wash hours}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 . Cook. And parlourmaid. You see, each had to take a - each week we took it in rotation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 This was the older girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, who were left school you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So one girl did all the cooking aided by somebody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well if there was a girl off school ill or anything like that she'd go in and help cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Otherwise it one girl doing the cooking on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 One girl. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 For twenty-five girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, yes. Oh the Matron used to - the Undermatron used to help her. And say we'll have so and so for today and - get everything ready for her and she used to do the - make the pastry, the cook, the Undermatron. She'd make - make pastry, but the girl w
ould have to do the potatoes and watch them - cook and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Quite a lot for the amount of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. And Sunday was a very busy day, least I should call it busy day because - we did - spent most of the day }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 changing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  our frocks. Everyt
hing was done on Saturday that could be done, and then of course there'd be the six o'clock - Communion service you have to put your best clothes - if you went, six, seven or eight. Then there's the eleven o'clock, you have to take your things off the min
ute you come back, take your best things off and put your second best on. Then if you went at eleven o'clock you used to have to change again, and then change when you come home again. Then if you went in three o'clock we'd change again, you know, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Catechism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 . Change again in the evening. Sunday was all -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You could easily change your clothes four times on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Oh quite. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You had three grades of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right. School -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that from your ordinary clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, no, we used to have navy and white - uniform, you see, and then we'd have - one one lot - a frock for - for school. And used to have a frock for - at home. Playing in, as they call it, play frock. Then you'd have one for best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So it was from your best into your play clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. Yes. Everyday frock they used to call it. And of course my - initials, I was called Helen then, I took over my sisters things. Hattie - Hettie. You see, H.K. Well I took her things and luckily her clot
hes fitted me. And I had her bedroom, her bed rather. And - even the nightdress cases had got H.K. on. Had nightdress cases then. But - what I - used to - used to worry me, in the winter - we only used to have this - two blankets at the most, and we had t
o take our - fold our - our counterpaines up every night, winter and summer, and put them on the end of the bed. And it used to be dreadfully cold. I used to hate the winter there you see, so 1 cold. Just the two blankets, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You couldn't have a hot water bottle or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, nothing like that, oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have bedsocks or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, nothing. No nothing. Just a nightdress. Even our best we used to have to take off, even in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were the nightdresses long with long sleeves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Oh yes, square yokes and - just plain flannelette.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was everything regulation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did everybody have the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, you had your own clothes. And you had to mend your own clothes too.-

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they give you the clothes when you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You didn't have any of your own clothes from previously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. Because you had to go into the uniform, what clothes you went in were - I don't know what become of those. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 You never saw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  them again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. 'Cos I had a - I can remember I went into a - a - what they call a princess - slip when I went, gym suit - gym - gym frock you know with the - box -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Pleats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, and a blouse underneath. But that -
 I never saw that again. You see. And in the winter we used to wear boots and in the summer shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have special shoes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No, no. No. And often we used to - in the winter - in the summertime we'd go for walks. Of course - 
crocodile fashion. School fashion. And - we'd go up one road, Hickley Road, come through the cemetery and home again, down Regent Road and home again. That's the outing. And - until you left school, and then went into the laundry as I said - well then wee
k
ends - there used to be a - a - a young chap about - I'd say about twenty - years old, used to bring - bring a wheelbarrow, at the back of - to the back gates, and he used to take the washing in the hampers back to the places where they - come from. The d
ifferent people we used to do the washing for. But - 'til the war broke out, and of course he was called up, so then us - us girls that had left school, we used to have to find the places and take the hampers out. Hampers then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you wheel them on a sort of trolley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, used to have to carry them. Carry them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They must have been very heavy weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
The big ones, I don't know what come - happened to the big ones. The very large hampers. They must have gone somewhere, bigger girls must have taken them or something, but anyway we didn't. We could manage the - smaller ones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you share the weight between two of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. One had one handle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A whicker basket would be an awkward thing to carry wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well no, not if there was two of you - all - more or less the same height. As if - unless went with a bigger girl and then of course it was awkward then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have to go quite long distances, about a mile or two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 On foot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Or could you go by tram?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, no - no trams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there trams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh there were trams, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But they wouldn't give you the money for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they let you talk to people who came to the orphanage at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh well my sisters used to come and see me, of course I could - talk to them, they used to come into the girls sitting room and talk to us. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that a regulation time of day they could come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, it was when
 their half day - half day used to be, they used to come and see me when I - on their half days you see. Used to come and take me out sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was quite all right was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. But the only time we had - anything different from bread and m
argarines and - a cup of tea for breakfast was Easter morning. And we used to have an egg then. We thought that was wonderful. Only time. And at Christmas. Christmas morning we'd have a - pork pie. And we thought that was wonderful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A pork pie for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. And then - sometimes in the summertime there'd be - one of the committee would send a hamper of apples. Oh we thought it wonderful to have an apple for - after our dinner. Oh wonderful. And - the committee used to give each girl on
 - Easter morning, a little - chocolate Easter egg. About the size - about the size of a hens egg. Of course I was lucky because I had two sisters out - at service and they used to bring me another one. But of course we'd have to share. Anybody that didn'
t have anything you know, or just that one - from the committee, we used to have to share. Our friends of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You mean any gifts coming in had to be shared?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that supervised, how would they get you to share?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. You
 had - each had your own drawer in the girls sitting room, and then she'd say, you give so and so some of that because she hasn't got any. Oh but in a nice way. You see, naturally you didn't mind. And I remember there was two little - three little girls u
s
ed - came to the orphanage, Tyrell their name was, three sisters. And their uncle and auntie used to have a - well I suppose a general store you'd call it and - they used to go - out - for a half day with these three little girls and they used to back and
 
often they'd bring a jar of jam or - or paste, meat paste. And they'd pass it round, any I pass it round? Used to have to ask first, may I pass it round, and - oh - when the jam come to you sometimes it was all gone. But anyway we used to watch this go - 
round and - oh - everybody -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have jam every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. Sometimes one of the big girls'd say - may we have some jam today please? And - otherwise we didn't used to - have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Really you had two meals - your breakfast and tea were mainly bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes, that was the menu. Yes. But sometimes on a Sunday we'd have a - a piece of cake, but not very often. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember ever feeling really hungry while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. Not hungry, but very - very - what sh
all I say - times when I used to think, oh it only I could talk to someone. And often I used to cry myself to sleep, and I know I wasn't the only one. But we daren't speak. You could hear the girl sobbing often.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You daren't speak because you were upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
We're not - allowed to you see upstairs. But - I remember when I left school and I was monitor. In the bedroom I used to - we used to have to go and see that the - blackout curtains were up as I told you, and - I remember getting in - the Matr
on's bedroom and - I was a monitor then, and she said, I'll wonder what they'll do when I - I leave, or when I go. This was the Matron. Well, I said, they'll never do - get anybody to do what you've done. And I said, why is it we don't have to speak when 
w
e get upstairs? Well, she said, Helen, that's not my rule. She said, that was given my - that was one of the rules when I took over this job as Matron, that was one rule that I was - made to - see that was kept. She said, I wouldn't have - I wouldn't allo
w it really. I don't hold with it, but, she said, that's the rule and I must keep it. So she said, that's one rule that you must keep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Did you ever talk to her about wanting someone to talk to and feeling a bit lonely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, well, no, no, we daren't. We daren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was a distance kept between you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes, you were - you were always kept as a group. Couldn't get - go individual and say, oh, I'm sorry, I've done so and so and - or can you tell me anything, you know. Some body to talk to and ask - ask about things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have to get that from each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. When I first went into the orphanage naturally - I hadn't a hairbrush I'd got a comb but no hairbrush. And I got upstairs and - undressed. Oh, I said,
 I've got - I haven't got a hairbrush, Annie, can you give me one? Sh, you mustn't talk. Why, I said. I couldn't make it out, not talking. I know one year we had - influenza went through the orphanage. And - well of course one after the other went down wi
t
h it. I had to sleep on the landing. My bed was on the landing. And - I was so lonely, I said, oh I don't like it up here, can I come in your room? Sh, you mustn't talk, and she reported me. I wasn't punished because I was on the landing, and I wasn't - I
 was new. Don't do it again - so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So you never used to talk in your bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. No. And we were always timed - our bathing was always timed. So many girls to so many - so long. And if we were any longer - Matron used to time us. The bel
l'd ring - and monitor would have to come up and see - who was in the bathroom how long you'd been here and who's next and who's next. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you had to share the water?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, three girls to one - bath full of water. I thought that was dreadf
ul. Couldn't have a bath you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When you went to service that was? And you say she didn't use that bathroom herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. Nobody used - nobody, not even the maid - not even the parlourmaid or any of them used to use it. I said, fancy having a bathroom and can't use it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So what you had to bath with there was just a footbath was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Is it like a washing up bowl type of size?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. You could just get your two feet in. It was a tin bath - with two handles one at each -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The big bath was only for Miss Ellis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes. That was always washed out every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So really you could only ever have a wash down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You never had anything like a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. You kneel on - on the mat and jus
t wash yourself down. I used to be so cold in the wintertime. I should never be clean, I never felt I was clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there any fire in that bedroom you shared with Jessie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No, no fire. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was it at the top of the house too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Was two storey - two storey house that one. Big square Georgian house that was, lovely house mind you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did the cook sleep in the house too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, the cook had a little room on her own - in the back - of the house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did you have to call Miss Ellis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Ma'am. Ma'am. Oh yes, ma'am. And you had to bob a curtsey when you - say, good morning madam. I often laugh at these things now, but - of course it would be so - serious at the time but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Had you learnt to curtsey before you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Because you had to curtsey to the committee. You see, on Christmas, as I told you, we were given a Bible - if we were good, if we had so many marks. I know this Christmas - I was given a Bible. That's the year I was - monitor. And - g
ood conduct that was for. And - as they gave you - each girl was given something useful, either a writing case - or a shoe - outfit, cleaning outfit, and a - sewing basket. Something very useful that you had to use. And as they gave it to you, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 thank you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  ma
'am, and you have to bob a curtsey. Oh dear. Another day's washing in my life. Oh. I shall never do another day's washing in my life. And I never have liked washing since. Ironing I did not mind, I liked that. But washing, no. I used to be so tired - with
 standing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Kneeling down a lot too I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, I wasn't very - I wasn't very tall you see and they were - they - they were about this size - up to this height you see. And we were standing in these - clogs and this apron. Used to have mackintosh apron and then this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Hessian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 one - on the top, standing in all this steam for two days, Monday and Tuesday. And then this dolly tub you see, you - dollying all the while. You used to have to take turns dollying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That dollying must have been tiring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Have you ever heard it called ponching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, that's a different thing altogether. You know the - where the sinks blocked up you have a - plunger? A sort of thing like that. Am - a - a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 poncher was. But you see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have that as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No, we just had dolly pegs. Called dolly pegs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Is ponching an alternative to dollying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, that's the next thing to that, you see. And I know on Saturdays - the whole of the morning was spent cleaning the whole pl
ace from top to toe. From one room right down to the very cellar. Every girl had her own work to do. Bedrooms, the landing, the sitting room, the girls sitting room, the kitchens, the - wash houses, the yards. And then the - laundry. There was little laun
dry and a big laundry. Everything had to scrub - be scrubbed and polished. And do you know, that was the hardest day's work. And yet we used to have the break - well - the dinner was bread and cheese - and hasty pudding.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What was hasty pudding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I don't know whether I can explain it to you, more like a - you know you make a white paste with flour and water? Well this was made with - flour and milk. It was like a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Sort of like glue?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes, I can't explain it, it was just like a 
paste. Then we used to have treacle with it. And used to - so hungry after you'd done all this scrubbing and cleaning. The day you wanted more you had less. I suppose they didn't have the time to do it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Could you have as much bread and cheese as you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, it was put on the table - on a plate. On your plate, yes. And the margarine was put in a little square on your plate - each put - the Undermatron used to give that out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that always the same at other meals too, there wasn
't as much bread as you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, just - the breakfast we'd have two pieces. That'd be equivalent to one slice now. We'd have to - that - that was for the younger ones, what the bigger ones - I don't remember what the bigger ones used to have. Bu
t we were all at the one table but theirs was up that end and us children down this end you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The twenty-five of you all sat at one table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. And the Matron used to have her own little table, the two Matrons. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Who sat at the head of your table then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The monitor. The monitor. The girl who was monitor take that place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So you did that for a while?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
For a little while but I - didn't like it because we were right in the dark, right in the draught of two doors. From the - yards to the girls sitting room you see, we were right in the middle of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was it the job of anybody to supervise the manners at the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we weren't allowed to talk unless we asked, we asked whether we may talk now. Yes, you can talk now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 At what stage were you allowed to talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When we'd finished - our meal. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Otherwise you ate in silence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. We had to say grace of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How was grace said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All stand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you all say it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, we all stand and - the Matron'd say that. Except on the - Christmas, then the vicar used to say it. 'Cos he used to come and have tea with Matron.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have grace before and after the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Always. And prayers of course - night and morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
At the meal was there anything you could ask for, could you speak to ask somebody to pass the salt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, if the jam was at that end and you wanted it, would you pass the jam please? And - she'd say - well there's n
o need to shout. It'll come on your end in a minute. You know, sometimes we used to get impatient and say, hurry up. Naturally. And all the water - for the washing - for - to go into the wash house was always used - a pump was always used for the water. W
asn't a tap. For the washing. Used to have pump this - pump the water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was a tap for drinking water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 At a meal could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Some of the big girls used to, not us little ones. Weren't allow
ed. But if there was - wasn't enough - one of the girls'd say - we've run out of bread Matron, could we have some more please? You see, sometimes there - there wouldn't be enough. Whoever was cook didn't - cut enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Suppose it was something you'd enjoyed, could you ask for some more?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes - for dinnertime - midday meal - I can remember the Matron used to cook the pastry, a slab of pastry in the meat tins, be big meat tins. And if there was any over she'd say, would any of you like any more? 
To clean it up. You see, and then whoever was up there first got the - until it was all gone and those - when it's gone you have to go back again to your seat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The governors sent fruit sometimes, was that the only time you had fruit?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Fruit, yes,
 yes. Fruit or custard or anything like that, not fruit and custard like we - do have tea here - these days. That was a luxury you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you did have a pudding at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes, pastry or - milk pudding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But not a fruit pudding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, no. Oh I say - no, I'm telling a lie. We did. One summertime I remember we had a - what they call a summer pudding. That was - a bazin - lined with bread, with the crusts all cut off. The fruit juice put in the bottom and then all kinds of summe
r fruit such as blackberries and - plums, all that, and there was three of those. For the twenty-five girls, mind you they weren't very big ones but there'd be three of those. And that was a real luxury, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have cream too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, we di
dn't used to have cream. No. No. And with - on our porridge in the winger - we used to have treacle. Black treacle. Black treacle, not - in - during the war that was, black treacle. Not sugar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You were twelve when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Before you went did anybody consult you as to whether you'd like to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh auntie did. Oh yes. She said - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Your aunt Emily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, my Aunt Lucy. Aunt Lucy that lived in Balaam Street. And - she said, you're going to a school. Naturally - 
you're going to a school with a lot more little girl and you'll be ever so happy and it's in the country. You'll se the trees growing, you'll see apple trees growing, which I hadn't seen, and I can remember my first holiday from the orphanage. Each child 
w
as a - allowed a week - out in to the country, and - she'd pick - one, two, three - three different places, little village and find different ladies that'd take us, say two at a time. And I remember going to Kirkby Muckslow and there was one of the commit
t
ee - Mr Rippon, that's right, and his wife was on the committee, and he - he - she used to invite us two - the two girls were in - that were at Kirkby Maxloe for tea one afternoon, afternoon tea. I can remember him coming home at half past five, and he to
o
k us down the orchard, and do you know that was the first time I'd seen an apple growing on a tree? I'd seen them in the shops but never on a tree. And I was twelve year old. And I remember he picked the biggest apple he could find - and I said, I shall n
e
ver eat all this, I couldn't manage it all - not before tea, but it was - oh I thought it wonderful to see apple growing. I simply stood in amazement - at these apples, see these apples growing. When I look - think back I think to myself, children now, if
 you told them that they wouldn't believe you. Well I'd never been out of London you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not even for a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I went - when I was with Aunt Emily we went down to - Ramsgate for a holiday. Went by steamer. Along the Thames. And I know they were all seasick but I wasn't. And they all vanished downstairs and I was on the top.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you stay in Ramsgate in a boarding house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. I slept on the floor. Yes, I slept on the floor then. And - my aunt had the bedroom, had the bed, and - I slept on the floor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your uncle go too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, uncle was in the fire station. He was on duty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was your Aunt Emily and another aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Another aunt. Two aunts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Your Aunt Lucy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. Aunt - oh - Elsie. Elsie. But whether sh
e was my real aunt I don't know but Aunt Emily was. But I used to call her Auntie Elsie, that's right, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You all had the one room there did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Aunt Elsie and Aunt Emily slept in one - in the big bed, I slept on the floor and gran had a room on her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Gran went too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, gran was there. Yes, because I kept with - I used to stay with gran, you know, I - gran was my companion. Aunties used to be - they were young I suppose and wanted go out in the evenings on their own. And - a
nd on the journey I remember - they all vanished. First Aunt Emily went, then Aunt Elsie went. Then grannie went I thought, where are they going? I learnt afterwards they were all seasick you see. And I was left on the top.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What did you do while you 
were at Ramsgate, do you remember anything about that holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I remember going on the sands. And punch and Judy was there. Which - I didn't like. Most children like Punch and Judy, but I - I used to be frightened, I used to - they used to be figh
ting. So - he was - I said, no, he's cruel, I don't like him. Oh I had some funny ideas when I was a child. I don't now, I don't like watching boxing or wrestling or anything like that or - or - rugby. Oh no, I didn't - gran used to - couldn't understand 
me, she said, you're a funny child, you - don't like Punch and Judy. And of course that was the done thing then for a child to see Punch and Judy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there any things like pierots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes, the - pierrettes and - the - banjos and such like 
with their straw hats and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they have blackened faces and that tupe of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, yes. Yes. And dance round you see, and the striped trousers and - coats, I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there the usual kind of thing they have on the pier
 now, round abouts and all that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I don't know, I don't remember that. No, I was never out long enough for that I don't think. I couldn't tell you. I couldn't tell you, the - I remember these pierrettes on the - on the pier, I remember seeing this 
- stage with these - sort of theatre, outside theatre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were on the sands who would be with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Gran. More or less gran.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She'd stay with you most of the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Gran, 'cos auntie - Aunt Emily and Aunt Elsie used to go up into t
he town and one thing and another. And - in the evenings gran used to stay with me, I should go to bed. And - the young ones used to go out naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You say you slept on the floor, did you have anything under you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A mattress. Oh yes, I had th
e mattress. Oh yes, and blankets, sheets and blankets. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When you were staying with your Aunt Emily you were also on the floor weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Ah, when - when uncle was off duty. He slept with auntie in the bedroom, you see. And I used to have my bedroom - bed in - in the living room, on the floor you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When he was on duty did you sleep with your aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. I slept with her then, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they have children of their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They - they did towards the end, she had -
 one little girl then. Well that's why I left because uncle used to blame - anything was wrong it was my fault. Yes. Auntie was - I used to love auntie, she used to do everything for me you know and - very kind, give me anything. But uncle - uncle was - I
 
don't know, he'd got a violent temper, and I know when I used to go to school - he'd give me some money to buy a - a paper - on my way, used to go through - Liverpool Street station, railway station, to school. And on my way through the station I used to 
h
ave to buy this paper. Newspaper. And if he'd lost on the horses - used to do a lot of betting I suppose - and I know one day I came home from school and I couldn't find auntie. Went into the bedroom-and she was crying bitterly. Of course I flew to her. W
h
at - ever is wrong, what's wrong auntie? Of course uncle had lost on the horses. And he'd come home in - upstairs in a temper and thrown her dinner at her. Oh, I said, he is a brute. Oh, I said, he is a brute. I said, I don't like him. And I never did lik
e him from that day to this. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 After that incident you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes, that stuck in my mind as a child, to think he'd - make auntie cry.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How had you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 felt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  about him before that incident?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh quite all right, he used to - be all righ
t, and then when the baby arrived - naturally - he thought the world of the baby. And anything wrong - it was my fault. I did it. He says, you've done that haven't you? You know, he used to fly in a temper at me. And I couldn't bear anybody to fly in a te
mper and I hadn't done anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How much older were you than the baby then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh - I'd be about I should say. Yes. Very sensitive, I was too sensitive really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You'd had a lot of hard knocks really hadn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I don't know but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But children hate that sort of thing don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, I don't like to be snubbed. Especially, I used to love auntie, think he was cruel to her, oh that was dreadful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What sort of particular things would he blame you for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He'd say - if the
re was - I remember particularly one Sunday morning, the milkman had been. And he came upstairs, and he said - you spilt that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 milks on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  the - on the step again. I said, me? I said, no, I didn't. He says, you have, don't answer me back. He blamed onto me, it
 wasn't me. It was either the ladle or the milkman had spilt it, you know - you see, but it wasn't me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The milkman would pour it into churns wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right - from the churn into the jug you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And the jug would be left on the doorstep would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And a few drops were easily spilt I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. And he used to blame me for little things like that that I - and if I didn't clean the buttons right, his buttons on his coat, mind you I was never allo
wed to touch his helmet. Used to wear brass helmets those days. The - only man that used to wear the black helmets was the men - called the salvage corps. Well they were allowed - they were supposed to - save all the furniture. Not the people. They saved 
t
he furniture, the salvage men, those in the black helmets. Those with the brass helmets used to - smash their way in to save the people. And put the fir out, you see. And - but he would never let me - I'd clean his buttons and his boots. But never let me 
touch that helmet, because the least scratch - because they used to be beautiful - brass. Wouldn't have a scratch on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Who cleaned it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
He did. Oh yes. I wasn't allowed to touch that. Because you see there'd be the coat of arms of the - hel
met. Used to look lovely when they were - all on the engine and see all these glittering - helmets you see. But nowadays they don't wear them do they? That's right, yes. That's right, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That time when he told you off about spilling the mi
lk is that the time when you left?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Went away. Yes, I went. In the evening they went out in the - uncle was on duty and auntie went out, and I was - I was told to put the baby to bed. Feed the baby and put it to bed. I fed the baby, undressed her, pu
t her to bed, in her cot, put the cot up. And put all my best clothes on. 'Cos I used to have some nice - lovely clothes there. Got them all out of the cupboard - drawers and one thing and another, and - put all the best things on. Went down - because - i
n the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 watch room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 there was glass, halfway you see. And I bent down so as uncle wouldn't see me, because I knew he was on duty, and it was raining when I got out there. Got outside. But I didn't care, I thought, no, I'm not stopping here. He's blaming me for
 everything. Of course I ran all the way home. From Blackfriars - from - Bishopsgate over to Blackfriars. To father's. And I can remember - just coming round - I must have collapsed when I got there because - father was sitting beside the couch. And he sa
i
d, are you better now? He said, what's the matter? And I said, oh I don't like uncle any more, I said, he's cruel. I said, he's cruel to auntie, I said, and he blames me for everything. He said, you're not going back there. And I didn't go back again. And
 of course the firemen were all out and the police were out looking for me. I was missing you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And the baby left all alone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. When auntie come home of course the baby - she was all right mind you.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She was understanding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ye
s. Oh yes. But I remember on the - I'd been home - a fortnight, and on the Wednesday - for some reason or other I went around to gran's which - as I told you, gran lived in the next street, in - Peabody Buildings. And auntie was there. And of course she b
u
rst out crying, she said, oh there you are, she says, what did you leave me for? And she wanted me to go back again, but I wouldn't. No. I wouldn't go back again. I said, no. She said, why not? I said, well I love you, but I don't love uncle. And she brou
ght all my clothes the next time she came to see gran, she brought all my clothes with - with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
So that wasn't the same time that you couldn't stay there because your father couldn't keep up the payments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, that was afterwards. That was the - no - that was the first time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
The first time you had to leave because your auntie couldn't afford to go on keeping you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, the first time I left was - 'cos - when I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The time you've just told me about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right. It was the
 second time - when - the baby was - arrived then. And I left gran's and went to auntie's and - auntie said, oh you'll have to go - this was uncle, he says, you'll have to go, he said, we can't keep you for nothing. So I remember him saying that. Can't ke
ep her for nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you think in fact they could actually have afforded it but he didn't want to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Who, my father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Your uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes, he was earning good wages then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It wasn't that they really couldn't afford it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was more that he just didn't want to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Didn't want me. I felt he didn't want me because they'd got the baby - you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your auntie say anything to you about it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, auntie didn't. Oh no. No, she was sorry I left. S
he wanted me to go back again. Oh yes. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But then after that second time you went back home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
I stayed - at home. Stayed home then. From there we went to - I told you we went to - Vincent Street and from there we went to Anne Street, back again to Plaistow. And from there I went to the orphanage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Having spent a little time with your Aunt Lucy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, before I went to the orphanage. Well that's the same with my brother, he stayed with Auntie Lucy for a little while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Have 
you any idea roughly how many months or years you were with Aunt Emily in those two stretches of time you were with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I should say about - two years, say a year in - in each - section. Yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you actually living with your gran?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh not very long, only about six months - in between. In between. Yes, that's right, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Except for those two spells with your auntie you were mainly with your father?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. 'Til I went to the orphanage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was he inclined to blame you for things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Who, my father? Oh no, my father, no, he thought the world of us. Oh yes. Oh yes, he - and we often say now - we've often said when we've - since we've grown up, I wonder why he never married again, having all those children. M
any men would have done. But of course there weren't many women to take on a whole family like that, and a crippled child in the bargain. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did he even keep Ernie with him after your mother died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, Ernie went with a - a Mrs Fieldhouse. 
Have I told you when - when I - I was in Guy's hospital? When I - that was be - after mother died. Or was it before mother died? That I couldn't tell you. I remember my brother - eldest brother, coming to fetch me home - from Guy's hospital, and I had a g
reen shade over my eyes. I couldn't see, I couldn't lift it in daylight or candle light.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
I don't know what was wrong. But it took a long long while to get better. And I - and - that's why I'm such a duffer I think, at school. My bro
ther - you know Balaam Street don't you? Well along - towards Forest Gate there's a hospital in between there, and they - where auntie used to live. And - dinnertimes - my brother was younger than I - should be - three to four years younger than I but - a
n
yway he used to go with me to this hospital and I used to have drops and ointment to put in my eyes, and of course he used to see me back to school. And of course I couldn't do the sewing, I couldn't do reading, I remember giving cottons out at - on the -
 sewing class, pink in one hand and blue in the other. And - they gradually got right again but - oh I was a long time before I could - do without this green shade over my eyes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Had you got rid of it by the time you went to the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes.
 Because I can remember auntie saying to - Miss Attwood, that was the Matron about having my eyes - tested. And - she said, well we'll find that out - when she's been with us a little while. And I never had anymore trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But it troubled you for some years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Oh yes. That's why I - I couldn't - that's why I'm such a duffer at - arithmetic or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Because you were handicapped in that way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. And I - at school I used to go down to help with the - with the infants, 
the babies, because I can remember in the afternoons we used to turn the tables upside down and fix canvas to each corner and the children used to go to sleep in the afternoon for an hour, 'til playtime. And then I used to get them up and take them - let 
them go out to play, and put the tables up again ready for the next lesson. I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that in Leicester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No, that was London. London, because I couldn't see, that was in Bear Lane school, I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You couldn't see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So they just gave you the job of looking after the infants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Looked after them and - yes, and - and do the messages, run the messages.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You actually couldn't see then?
