No, no, not the back licorice. Like a root. Root of a tree. And it was licorice. Licorice root. And you'd chew and chew and chew. In - strips perhaps, ah as wide - wide - thick as my finger and about that
 length. You'd get so many for a penny or a ha'penny, whichever you had and then locust beans. They were shape of banana, shape like a banana but flat, and very dark brown. And there was beans, hard beans inside these. Used to eat - eat the outer - outsid
e
, it was like a - banana skin flattened but - brown. Very hard. It was sweet, that was sweet, but you couldn't eat the beans, the beans that were inside it, which'd be the seed I suppose, for the next - locust beans and - licorice root, honeycomb - and of
 course the Spanish - things that we used to - we get now, but those are the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Spanish is licorice?
