Licorice powder. I think everything else was the same as they do - get now. A lot of the things are coming back aren't they, aniseed balls and that sort of thing, they're coming back now, we used to have them. And - oh another game we used to play with bo
n
ds, the boys used to call bonds. Little tiny things - in the - shape of a bomb, no bigger than a - what shall I say - a thimble. And you - open the - they're in half, you open it, put your cap in - and it's on a string and you drop it and it - explodes. Y
ou don't see those now. They used to call those bombs, that's boys - used to frighten everybody. No, I think that's all. In games and songs. Just outside a tiny cottage, stands the father of the child. \{BLANK\}
 He has heard his baby pleading, for her darling
 brother to come home. With a sigh to her he gently whispered, with a sob he clasped her to his breast, I will love you Lily always, little darling's heart now be at rest. And then you sing the chorus, up a bit high for me at the moment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Just another Fatal weddings it's called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, that's what it chorus, yes. Do you want it? Just - now where are we - While the wedding bells were - not that isn't the one. And a little child shell lead them, lead them gently on life's way, and a little c
hild shall teach them, how to love more dearly every day. And will bring them close together should they ever care to stray, she is an angel sent from heaven and will surely lead them on their way. I just can't get it at the moment. Desks they used to use
 
at school. Nowadays they have - tables with - that seat about six. Whereas in my time there was one long hall and you each had your own - you turned the desk up - the lid of the desk turned up - altogether, a long row, and there was your own individual pl
ace. And you had slates and - and - slate pencils, not - books like they do now.
