\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your mother serve it from the pot she cooked it in or did she 
put it onto dishes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh I don't remember that. I don't remember that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember how Aunt Emily did her serving up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well of course she served uncle first. Oh - oh she had vegetable dishes on the table. If we needed anymore we could always have it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember who you used to play with when you were a child, were they children just nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, just my - school - friends. I remember one day we were playing skipping - a girl - her name was Annie Pickett, I do
n't know why I remember that but - this particular - thing I suppose makes me remember it, we were skipping. And we were eating sweets at the time, and one got lodged in her throat, and she died. It choked her, yes. I can remember that as plain as - and s
h
e was the first person - I ever saw - in her coffin. I wouldn't go at first but - her mother said, oh you must see Annie. And I thought how beautiful she looked. It was all padded inside and there was - violets, violets and little tiny daisies. Oh she did
 look lovely. I thought, oh she's like a little angel. We were only tiny, I should think I'd be about seven - or so then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Who were you staying with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Aunt Emily. Yes. We were skipping then you see and - of course - all of a sudden she - shudd
ered and went to the floor. Well of course naturally we ran for her mother but - she was taken away but she died. Just got lodged in her throat, that's why I'm always afraid of my children would - giving them hard sweets. While they're running around, but
 of course children more - used to it nowadays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How did it come about that you saw her in her coffin, were you invited over?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, they said, you must - I said, no, I didn't want to do it. I said, I've never seen anybody and naturally I was a 
bit frightened as a child. She said, well you come with me. And I can see the coffin now, with a candle each end. A light. And she looked so lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you just taken over on your own by her mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, taken upstairs and all had to be very quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you think her other school friends went and saw her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes, most of them did that we were playing with at the time. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you didn't go to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No, I didn't remember that. That's the first one I've eve
r seen, that was the first one I ever - person I'd ever seen dead of course. And I suppose that's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You didn't see you mother dead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. Well I don't remember anyway if they did show it me, I didn't - don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you actually play with your sisters or were they too much older then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we all played together. Yes, yes, we'd play together, yes. And I can remember one of my elder sisters always read to us on a Sunday. Yes, because - we weren't allowed to play on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that Hettie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Hettie or Jessie, I don't know which. One of those. But we weren't allowed to play - and go out in the streets on a Sunday. Had to sit in the parlour and - read your book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So she'd read aloud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, she'd read to me. All different stories, that I could understand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Like school prizes and that sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I suppose so, I presume, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Was there one of your sisters or Ernie that you felt particularly close to or did you feel much the same about all of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I was close to Dolly. My cripple sister. There was only thirteen months between us, you see, and she - she always clung to me more than the others because we were together most. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you went out to play were you allowed to get dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well - we got - as ordinary children do get dirty but - Aunt Emily was more strict - on that - score.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 More strict than gran?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. Gran was a bit - you know, give way to me more. Like all grandmas do. Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, they say I spoiled my grandchildren but I said, that's grandmother's privilege.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember actually being punished for getting dirty, there was the time she dressed you all up to go out wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ah yes, on a Sunday, that was on a Sunday, and
 she was going up to see uncle then. I suppose while they were courting that would be you see, 'cos uncle wasn't a - he was in the fire brigade but they weren't married I don't think you see, and she used to take me up with - to her and uncle used to sit 
r
ound the fire engine for a little while they were talking and then - he put his hand in his pocket and give me sixpence. He'd say, go and get some sweets. Well of course that's while they wanted to talk together naturally. And of course I wouldn't know th
at. And he said, spend it all, he said, spend it all. I thought, oh lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever have a bicycle when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh - no. No, never had anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever have a bicycle at any time in your young days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I didn't, No. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They were rather more of a luxury then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh they were, yes, was only the really the gentry or those - rich people used to say. Father's in good - positions at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was a big difference then wasn't there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. If you were poor you were poor. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were a child did you think of yourself as being poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, I just took it natural you know, and didn't seem to worry me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You were saying there were the rich and the poor, yo
u didn't think of that when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not as a child, no. The only thing I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When did it start to dawn on you that there was such differences in life?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well when - when you didn't get anything to eat you know, when things were very 
bad. And I could see these other children nicely dressed and I thought, oh - what a lovely frock she's got on, and then she had something nice for her lunch, you know, the midmorning break. We wouldn't have any. I'd think, well why is that? And I used to 
think, oh 'tis 'cos dad's out of work. You see. That was my opinion anyway but - how Jessie put it over to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you speak to Jessie about these things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. I talked to her when she was home - in fact this year. Did she remember, she s
aid, you don't know what I went through, she said, I - seeing you children without anything, but, she said, that's why - she left home. She felt she had to go and - do a bit. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 At that time there was a big difference in the way children dressed was there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes. I mean - there's one little girl, she's very nice little girl she was, Winnie Bunting her name was. And she had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She was the one with the biscuits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, and she had long ringlets. Long - golden hair, really 
golden hair. And she used to play the piano and I thought, oh her mother must - have plenty of money to be able to let her play the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember being brought up to treat rich people or people of a different sort of way of life differently from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, we always were learnt to respect them you know and - say, yes ma'am, and thank you very much ma'am and - especially at the orphanage, always. Oh yes, if you didn't - yes ma'am, and no ma'am, and - more or less - bob a curtsey when
 they gave you the prizes or anything, give you anything -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Had you been taught to say ma'am to people be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 fo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 re you went to the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, no, we'd say, thank you and - always say please and thank you but - not to that degree anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 D
o you remember in those years before the first war hearing people referred to as real gentlemen or real ladies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well my mother used to say he - he's a - often used to say, right gents around, I've heard him talking to my - eldest brother. What was hi
s name? Oh dear. And he said you didn't have to - speak to them, those that got in the cab, he used to drive one of those - what they call hansome cabs, where the driver sits right up at the top, two wheels. And - they have a little - flap that used to op
e
n to talk to their passengers. And - he said you didn't have to speak unless they knocked that - flap, and he would open it and - yes sir? And where do you want, and suchlike. Often used to talk to - Will and say what - I've had to drive so and so to - th
e theatre or maybe to a - so and so's house, you see, Hyde Park or somewhere like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And he'd know who the people were you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, he'd know their name - because they were well known people. Yes, that's right. Hyde - Hyde Park area and - where's the other one - Finsbury Park, round that area. Right away from us naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A lot of very rich people lived around Hyde Park and Finsbury Park?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, that is the area - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Those were big houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They're still up some 
of them big places, yes, some of them are. Berkely Square and - you've heard of Berkeley Square. Pall Mall. At the top of Pall Mall. And Rotten Row, I've heard him talk of Rotten Row. Where the Queen Mother's house is - no - the Mall, the Queen Mother's -
 house is in the Mall isn't it, Clarence House. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But if he said somebody was a real gentleman what exactly did he mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well he'd have to doff his - cap to them, and he'd give him a good tip. He'd say, oh I got so and so, he said, that was Lord so and so. He'd call it Lord so and so whether it was Lord so and so I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember people using the term real lady, do you know what they actually meant by it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well Auntie - Aunt Emily - would say - I've got so and so
 coming to see me now, you sit still and don't speak until you're spoken to. And I used to think, oh she must be a lady. Whether she was or not I don't know but I used to class her as - upper. Yes. Upper class and the lower class.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you think of it as upper class and lower class at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Because she was dressed differently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You tell so much more by how people were dressed then could you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, yes. You watch people going by and say - we used to - as I told you we used to 
sit in this - alcove in this public house, we used to watch them going by you see. Say - hmm, she's - she comes from so and so. No, she doesn't, she comes from our way, 'cos she had - she's got a skirt right on the floor. It was dirty. You see, the lady -
 a lady'd have a clean one every day. Whereas a - another one wouldn't bother you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's changed now hasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, a good change I think. Good change. And then if we were singing in that alcove and the people came along from the saloons
 going out - they'd perhaps give us a penny, say, that was very nice, and - and - give us a penny. Oh that's champion, we used to say, that's champion. And then - everybody else go out and think, oh they're nothing, they're nothing. They're nothing.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you think at that time it was possible to move from one class to another?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Yes, if you tried hard - I mean, if the men worked hard - they worked up. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And also to move down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, like father did, he went down instead of m
y - his brothers - made money and got on well. And didn't want to know us because we were down. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You never visited them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. Oh no. Only Uncle Arthur and Aunt Lucy's husband.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He was a brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 My father's brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He was a wheelwright?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So did you feel they were in a different class at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. Yes. We weren't allowed to go around there unless Aunt Lucy asked for us, you see. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But she was kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you never met the others, the other brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, no. No, I wouldn't know my other uncles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I wonder why Uncle Arthur was different from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well that's why I met - how I met him through Aunt Lucy you see. The others I didn't. You see - - 'cos - they left us you see, and of course they lived in a different area to what we did. You see as - as they got up they lived in a different area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you know where they did live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 One lived at Forestgate. They had a garage,
 he finished up with a garage. And - that was Uncle Perry as I called him. And the others, I don't know where the others lived. I lost -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They lived in better off parts of London did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. They lost a - a son, one of them lost a
 son I know with the - first world war. Because I remember my father saying, one of your cousin's have gone. But who it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But it was a cousin you never knew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No. I don't remember seeing them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You went to church in your family didn't you, you were Church of England?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Were you aware of people going to chapel and being different from church people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, that's the funny thing, I've been thinking of that, we didn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you know any people who went to chapel?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember any clergymen calling on your aunt or ever having anything to do with the clergy at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
We did at the orphanage of course, they used to come every week, once a week every week for the Bible - Bible lesson, but - Aunt Emily's let me see - no, I don't - remember there, not at Aunt Emily's. Not gran's, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So really your first contact with people like that was at the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes, that's where I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have to call him sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
What about schoolteachers, there was that one who was kind and asked if you'd had your dinner wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Ah, I don't - I don't know her name. But I do remember the first one - the other teachers, there was 
Miss Crush, Miss Knott, Miss Hat, Miss Dury. And I told you we made up a rhyme about them. Miss Drury and - Mr Pickard and - Mr Gosling. But - otherwise I don't remember the ladies - the teacher's name that gave you the biscuits but - I can see her sittin
g at her desk now and - I suppose I was late - going out and doing my sums over again you see that I'd - got wrong. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 At that time where would you have placed the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh we had to respect them. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But were they the rich or the poor or the upper class or the lower class?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we'd think they were - upper because they - teachers were very - good, we thought oh they were - they must be rich - to be teachers. You see? Well of course you do, I mean you've got to have - t
here's all the - the apprenticeship and all that, there's - you've five years of your life gone even now isn't there for teaching. Oh it's gone down? Oh I see. Well I mean that's a lot - that's a lot out of your life to - and expensive time too. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
What about the shopkeepers, did you have anything to do with them, how would you treat a shopkeeper in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh we'd have to say please and thank you but - as a right, we'd just go and ask from what we want and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You wouldn't call them sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember being brought up to think of some families as being rough and others as being respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. We weren't to play - allowed to play with the rough ones, I wasn't anyway, not when I was with gran.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What distinguished a family as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well, ragged and - and dirty and they used to fight, you know, fight and - swear too. Anybody swore oh they - they were rough ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you were kept away from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did your father also keep you away from rough children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Oh yes. Weren't allowed to - mix with all - all and Sunday but - but we weren't often out when I was with father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you said Vincent Street was a very rough area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. We wouldn't go out to play
 there. No. The only time - I remember we - were out once and that was near Christmastime - and father - or I'd lost my key or father had, or he was late home anyway, 'cos I remember - looking at the toy shops and one thing and another, and keeping warm a
t the - there's a - next to the - two or three doors away from the toy shop was a - what do you call them now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A grille, a kind of grating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes, a cafe of some sort, and they had a grating and the heat used to come up and we used to stand there and get warm. Then we'd say, oh let's go and look at the toys again. 'Til father came home and then it began to get dark and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
What about this little girl Winnie, what job would have her father have done that they were so much better off, do you know what her father's job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No I don't know, but - oh, I - yes I do, he had a bakers - bakery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 He had his own business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. Yes. And she was the only child. She had lovely clothes, always had shoes, lovely shoes, all sh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11339072\charrsid675430 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 ne - 
all clean. She always looked clean. And I remember at school always allowed - we always had to show our hands, to see if our nails were clean, and hands were clean. And - the next school I went to - the teacher said, show your hands. Naturally I put my ha
n
ds out and she said, what are you doing? I said, you want to see my hands. She said, not like that child. You had to fold your arms so that your hands come there, I can't do it now, fold your arms behind so as your fingers - so. And show - show your finge
r
s - I - I can't do it now but I used to then. Show hands. And used to - and - that was to keep your shoulders back and sit up. And she had a little stick about the length of your - microphone there, and - if you didn't sit up, she'd - being you on the bac
k with this - stick. Oh.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Which school was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That would be Broad Street I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were staying with Aunt Emily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember Winnie's mother as being different from the other mothers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I 
never saw her, no. No. But we always - us other children used to let her go first. I don't know any, but we did, we used to let her go first. Whether we were shy or - frightened or what I don't know, but - used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there any other children that were as well off as she was that you knew?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, quite - quite a few, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was at Bear Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So there was quite a mixture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, mixed school because the - girls had one playground and the boys had another. They didn't have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Socially it was fairly mixed too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The standards of living were quite different were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember times when you were better off, like when you were with Aunt Emily or your father was in work, thinking - feeling sorry for other children who were poorer than you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, I realized then that I was lucky. 'Cos I always had nice clothes there and I used to look - you know - I used to be like that. I never though
t I'd go back to it. When - when I - did leave Aunt Emily and went back to grandma, I'd been away a fortnight then, and - as I told you, they had the police out and one thing and another to find me, she bought all the clothes with me - with her. Yes, all 
my nice clothes - all the nice clothes. I thought - often think, well - another person wouldn't have done nowadays, they'd think, well she's gone and that's that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Do you remember people making a distinction between craftsmen and labourers, a man who'd served his apprenticeship and a man who didn't have a trade at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well one was the boss and the others were the workers. More or less. If you were a porter at the - at the railway station you were just - a worker. And then the guards - man, w
ell he was above you naturally. And they'd say, yes sir. The others had to respect him. Even at that - level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 There was a big social distinction in the working class itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were a child at Blackfriars or with Aun
t Emily do you remember being aware of who were the most important people round about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, we knew the Lord Mayer - was somebody grand. That sort of thing. We knew that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But not beyond that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It wasn't like in a village where the vicar is important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. Although - when the vicar used to come to school we always had to call him sir. And we weren't spoken - we never spoke to him unless he spoke to us. Oh yes, we didn't mix with him. They - he was one of the upper class - 
class as you might say then. Nowadays they mix with the people more don't they. They've got to otherwise they won't get the people will they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about doctors, did you have any doctors who used to call or anything?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Doctor. No, I don't think I remember - any doctors coming. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you ever remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, in Bishopsgate. They didn't - go out on their cars and motorbikes like they do now. They used to have to walk in - single file
, and there'd be about a dozen. As they come to one area - two'd branch off to that area, that's their - was their beat, and two'd go that way. And two another, 'til all - they were all used up. Yes. But no cars, no bike - no bikes or anything like that. 
The only - car we used to see was the Black Maria, then we knew somebody had been wicked and they were taken to prison.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you ever remember seeing the police arresting people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh I can remember seeing - one man. Only one man, I remember seeing t
hem put him on the stretcher. There's no ambulances like - there are today. There was just these stretchers in different huts along the road. And whoever - police was on that - duty there, that area, they'd unlock this door and - get the - stretcher out a
n
d - I can remember seeing them running along the road - and it's only just two wheels, I'll tell you where I saw one, in - Sandown, Isle of weight, in the museum there. It was up in the corner, I said, that takes me back some years, when I was a child tha
t - and it had got the hood on just - as though - exactly - like they used to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Why was this man you saw put in the stretcher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
I don't know. Don't know whether he was drunk or - or whether he was taken ill or what but I remember them lifting hi
m up and putting him - on this stretcher as I used to call it, and they wrapped him in a grey blanket then, and put this hood up and away they went. I suppose to the nearest hospital or if he was drunk they'd take him to the prison.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were a ch
ild did anybody say to you, I'll call a policeman, if you were doing something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh they used to say, I'll tell a policeman if you don't - if you - policeman would be after you, but - there was one man used to come - used to work at the - powder facto
ry. Yardley's - I don't know whether it - no, Cherry Blossom, Cherry Blossom factory, and he had a wooden leg. And of course boy like - used to watch the boys, used to go after him, peg leg, peg leg, and there used to be a policeman waiting round the corn
e
r - evidently he'd spoken to the policeman about it, and the policeman used to flick those boys ears as they got to the corner of the street, this man used to - never used to take any notice 'cos he knew they'd be - they wouldn't come right near him. He k
new how far they were behind him. He used to get round - just round the corner and then - a policeman'd come round. Just clip their ears with their hand - with their gloves. We thought that was dreadful. They'd run then, the boys'd run then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember what that man's name was with the peg leg?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, I don't. And we used to know it was always six o'clock. Always six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When he came along?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes. And boys - than in those days - was - another mischief they used to get up to. Th
e - carts, as you know, or the cabs, didn't go very fast. And they'd go behind the cabs and get on that little - bar at the back. Like a - a car has a bumper well that was on the back of these carts whichever they were, either the water carts and - and th
e
 boys used to sit on there. And then the other'd say, whip behind guv'nor. And of course he'd - swish his whip you see and - they'd have to clear off. They couldn't do that now with the traffic like they are - like it is now. The same when the water carts
 
used to come along - in the very hot weather. They don't do that now but - they'd be - have the spray, sprinkler at the back, sprinkler, and sprinkle the road, and the boys used to get behind it, take their socks and shoes off and - run behind and have a 
cooler. A shower. And of course the others'd call to the man, and of course he'd whip this whip round and - they'd have to get off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did girls ever do that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No, girls were - that was above us. Beneath us girls to do anything l
ike that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How do you think the police treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh not too bad, not as far as I know, I've never seen - I've never seen anybody - you know, being roughly treated by a policeman or - or being arrested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You weren't in fear of the police as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. But we knew we had to behave, if we saw one - coming along, a policeman. We'd have to behave. But other wise we - we weren't afraid of them. No. I wasn't anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 All the homes you had were rented weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there ever a landlord that you saw much of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh when I was with gran - when I was with gran he used to come every week, and Aunt Emily's - their flat went with the job. With uncle's job you see. Like my husband's. Used to have the house on the farm you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So at Aunt Emily's there wasn't a person coming round collecting rent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No, just at - gran's I remember. And of course Jessie used to take our rent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She used to have to take it somewhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Don't remember him coming - up there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you remember any feelings about your landlords at all when you were a girl?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, not as a child, if - it was the landlord it was the landlord you know. Ordinary tradesman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you ever remember anybody making a
 terrific did outside anybody else's house with a lot of tin cans and kettles and things to drive them out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, I don't remember that. No, only at Vincent Street, that was a - they used to scream and - weekends used to scream, come home drunk and - shout murder and one thing and another and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But not people organised banging tins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, no, not in gangs, no, no. No. Only the boys up to mischief tying - cans to the - cats tails and suchlike, I've known that. Little demons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 They used to come round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right. Oh yes, the boys used to have them - little barrows with the ties on, oh yes, they used to have those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Collecting, penny for the guy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was not girls again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no, no. Not gir
ls. No, we'd have the windmills, we'd play the - make the wind - mills, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 I'd like to ask you a bit more about when you were with Miss Ellis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh the quakeress. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there a servants hall at that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No, we used to have - our meals in the kitchen. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was the only place you could sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's all. Yes, or upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you feel at ease with Miss Ellis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. I had to behave myself and - be out of the way while she was anywhere around. Unless of course I was serving the meal - naturally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you feel at ease with the other servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I got say - mind my manners with them. And talk to them - they used to talk to me naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Would you say you felt relaxed with them though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well I didn't at first. Until I got used to them, then I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
When you were there would you say you were lonely or did you have enough companionship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well I hadn't anybody to talk to of my own age. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Do you actually remember feeling lonely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well I felt they were - too old for me, you know. I couldn't open my heart to them and ask them questions, like I used to often think, well - I used to go to my sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You could tell them your worries and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you ever feel homesick there or at the orphanage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh at the orphanage I did. Oh yes, yes. Night after night often we used to think - there'd always be one of the girls crying. You hear - hear them crying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But not at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Miss}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  Ellis' you didn't feel homesick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. Yes, because she used to have the - wounded soldiers in for - afternoon tea. In the gardens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
So you were there when the war ended and didn't leave her 'til the following year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The next year. Then I went to this - oh what was it - Taylor, Mrs Taylor.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How many years were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I think I was there about eighteen - or two years, because - they took me away with them to - Wales, as companion to the - a nanny I suppose. Family - childrens nurse a
s was, but of course she was over seventy then, and needed someone to look after her, while the others went away you see, went out. I - used to sit with her in the mornings on the sands, and then in the afternoons - it was her that taught me crocheting an
d suchlike. Always had to be doing something. Either knitting or crocheting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you get married from that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No, I went to - Tyler's - when did I go to Tylers? Oh I had a month at - with my sister in - in the factory. 'Cos Jessie was in
 a - as I told you on munitions, and then she went into this factory, Fair - Fairbrothers in Leicester. Fairbrothers, they used - to make - braces, mens braces. She said, why don't you come in with me and - in the factory. Well I hadn't been - been in a f
actory in my life. Oh dear, the noise of the machines and the - language of the girls, swearing and suchlike. It was awful, I - well it opened my eyes really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You had not mixed with people like that before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. And - fancy talking like that, and 
- oh I couldn't get - no, I was only there a month, because - my sister had been there so long that she was used to the machines, they were all electric you see and once you put your foot on the - pedal and your work was gone. And I had to make - I was on
 
a binder as they call it, and I used to do - have to do a hundred and forty-four pieces to one dozen. Then you only got one and threepence a dozen. You see. Well at the end of the week - I was only earning twenty-seven shillings and my board and lodgings 
was twenty-five. You see, and sharing room with my sister as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It wasn't worth it really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, oh I couldn't do it, I couldn't stand the noise, the machines were going all night. You see, so I left there. Where did I go from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was some kind of sewing machine was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was a - yes - yes. And that was stitches and bind - linen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Where did you go from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Let me see, where did I go from there? I think that's when I went back to service, Mrs Tyler's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You went back to her again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, no, that's when I went to there. Yes, I think that's there. From there. And then - where did I go, oh Miss Tollett's. Tolletts in - Murtonfield Road, Leicester. He was J.P. then. He was J.P., he was really upper class. That - th
at was only - one, two, three of us there, no, four. Edith - no, three of us there. A houseparlour maid, myself and the cook. That was a nice place too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh I must have been there about - oh I should say from two years -
 onwards. Two years onwards. And then from there - I left - I was out of a job. I don't know how I come out of a job but anyway - from there - I met my husband's sister - ah, the - the girl I used to share a bedroom with there, Nora, took me up to her you
n
gman's house. And there was fourteen children in the family. And there was - I can remember the first day I was there. The mother was washing, it was on the Wednesday, my half day. She said, would you like to get the tea for me? I said, oh yes, I don't mi
n
d. Well, I said, where's the tablecloth? She said, oh we don't have a tablecloth. No tablecloth? 'Cos it was a polished table, it was a big oval table. No, she said, we don't have a tablecloth. All right. So I said, where's the bread? Well I out up two so
lid l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11339072\charrsid675430 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
aves. Two. And put them on the plate. I said, what do they have with it? Well, she said, you can put that basin of dripping out and, she said, that pot of jam. Well naturally I thought it was the little pot, instead of that it was one of those big - b
ig jars you see, a six pound jar. She said, put that on the table. Well to see those children eat. That - two loaves were gone in no time. And they used to wear boots then. The father was as - bootmaker you see, and - when we'd cleared that lot out and th
e
 children used to go out to play. As the older ones were coming home from work - say well that's ; now let me see, there's - Arthur, Logan, Edgar, Charlie - oh - oh I don't know, about seven of them anyway, and - she said, well so and so's dinner's the fi
rst one, I used to - there was a flap on this - open range and there were - with a shelf, and each dinner was - seven dinners there. So and so's was first and then - as they come in I used to get their dinners out and put them on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She was very well organised was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, yes. But - oh dear, see these children - think, well when - when they going to finish. And every child come home - the father had a big bench this side of the house, this side of the room with all his tools you see, 
shoemaking tools and - they all used to have to change their shoes and put their shoes out - or boots, whatever they were, some had shoes, some had boots, underneath this bench, and put their old ones on to go out to play. Oh what a lot of shoes. It remin
d
ed - reminded me of the orphanage you see. And then when the big ones come in of course they had dinner - their tea rather. And their dinners, they had dinner at night 'cos the children used to come home for midday dinner. I remember on the Sunday I went 
t
here Sunday one day. And - teatime came. We were all in the front room. Or all us older ones, such as myself, had to go in first. And the young men and - girls - all sat round the table. And then the mother'd say, now you young ones, you can come. So as w
e
 got up there was a scramble. Who was going to sit in the - so' and so's place. And when - even when I was married I remember taking my two children there. Was-the mother there? No, the mother and father had gone then, mother and father had died. The elde
s
t daughter was taking - taking over the family there. Naturally my children had - used to have another plate for their sweet. Well they had their first course. And Mary, her name was, come on she says, get on with your pudding. Well, he says, I want anoth
e
r plate. This was Maurice, my second son. Oh, she said, you'll get - take that piece of bread and wipe your plate round, you use the same plate. But he wouldn't. No, he wouldn't have his dinner - unless he had another plate. She said, you've got to get us
e
d - you wouldn't stay for a holiday here, you do the same as we do. We wouldn't allow for - weren't used to - too much washing up I suppose. And I remember when he was ill once, when we were staying there. She said - do you remember the fish kettle? With 
a
 big - handle. I used to do two roly-poly puddings as they called them. One - with jam in, and another one with onions if you please and the bacon. Instead of putting the jam and rolling them up, you put bacon and - the - jam and onion - the - bacon and o
n
ion. And we - and tie them up the ends and put them both in this fish kettle, leave them to boil. And I'd make a big bread pudding in a big - meat tin. And that'd all go. And it used to take me all morning to do the vegetables. Vegetables and these puddin
gs. Oh dear, I was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But that wasn't how you met your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. In - in a way it was because - his - sister used to lodge there. You see, and I was out of a job then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She had lodgers too as well as all those children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes. 
Oh yes. She said, oh there's always room for more. And she said, if - that was when - I hadn't got anybody then, Nora took me up there and - my other sisters, Jessie wasn't married. I don't know where Hettie was. Anyway this - Bella said - look, she said,
 
my lass, she said, there's always room for one more, she said, if you ever want any up come up here, this is your home. She was a wonderful woman. But anyway, I was telling you, Rose was there. She said, we want a dormitory maid at our - at Bedford. Oh, I
 
said, I couldn't do that. I'd only been a between maid or something like that you see at the time. Oh she said, I'm sure you could, she said, you can scrub can't you? I said, yes, I can scrub. She said, and make a bed? I said, yes, of course I can. So any
way I went. I left }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Leicester}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
 then and went. I wished I'd known the job first - you know, a long while. And I was always allowed in the childrens day nursery because she was nurse - to the master's children you see. And there was only myself allowed in the d
ay nursery, with the children, none of the other maids were allowed - in the day nursery, and - I could go out with nurse as well. She was always called nurse you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So you had a friend there as well as quite liking the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. And 
there was eight - eight of us there in the - servants quarters, there was eight servants then. We had some fun there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I wasn't there very long. I was only I should say a year at the most. And of course - my husband used to see his - come and see his sister, that's how I met him, you see. Went out together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you there 'til you got married?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, I left there and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 After you got married did you take a job straight away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh no. No, I
 didn't take a job 'til; oh - the boys were quite - about eight year old I should think when I first took a job. But it was too much for me, I couldn't do the two together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that when you were doing the dairying work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Which was really with your husband's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Yes, it went - went in with Alec's job. Yes. Like they do now, a - husband - would do his ordinary job and the wife would help - in the house. Husband and wife job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But your duties were the dairy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
In the dairy work, yes, bottling and - sterilizing the - the - separator and suchlike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that more or less full time work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. I used to go in the morning at six 'til nine. And then from three 'til six in the evening. Hard work while you were at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you had your own house to look after didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. It was too much for be because I collapsed. My father was with me at the time. And he said, now, he said, it's no good. I remember having the doctor then. And he said, no, he said, she's overworking. It's too much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long did you keep on at that work until you collapsed like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, my - husband had to leave. Because that came in that work you see. That was only that one house you see for the - cowman and his wife. Of course we had to go out you see, had to move there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long had you been doing that dairy work before that happened to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh - not long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 A year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh at the most. The most. Yes. And then we went to Northampton whe
re Maurice was born, and that was another job where I had to go in the dairy. Well I - stuck that 'til - before - just before Maurice was born, 'til I realized he was on the way. 'Cos I collapsed then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You collapsed again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. In the snow one 
Christmas. I can remember the eldest one, he was about four then. Hardly four because there's three - two and half years between each one, and I remember him saying - are you better now mummy? And my husband - he went and fetched my husband I suppose. And
 from then on I - I didn't take any work. Then we had to move again you see because there was only the one house. It made such a lot of moves you see. The same with - at - at Four Elms, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid868964\charrsid675430 Kent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 , you see, my husband had to move from one farm to another - 'co
s they wanted - one farm was like a nursery. When - if the cattle claved or were ill they were sent up to this Ide Hill Farm. So of course we had to move from one - perhaps lower farm up to the higher - higher farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Because he had to carry on looking after the cattle you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 More or less - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7365922\charrsid675430 veterinary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430  work as well you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you never had to do any work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not there, no. Not there - no. Oh no, I couldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you never do any work after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not after that. No. Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long were you in the Northampton job before you collapsed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh I'd been about - eight to nine months, I know, because there was only myself and another young person in the village - and more or less it was - Gutteridges and - Cutteridges
 and - and - another name. One was intermingled - the families - it was always like - just the two families, in the whole village. Generation and generation. And like it his young person and myself were the old - the youngest ones in the village. And we u
s
ed - they used to say, there go the modern ones. Just - we used to go out together you see. There go the modern ones, 'cos we'd got our hair bobbed you see then, that was all the fashion, which was the latest then. We - they - they mixed - the Gutteridges
 
and - that just remains, Gutteridge is one, that sticks in my mind, and then there was another one, another name. And either - either that was my uncle or that was my sister - my cousin or - so and so. And we used to - my house was - my cottage was the la
s
t one in the village. And - I had to go there was only one pump. For water. And that was in the centre of the village. So of course I had to go down the hill to the centre of the village to get every pail of water I needed. And wash day I used to carry my
 
baby in one arm and bucket in the other, and often when you got down there in the wintertime there'd be no water. No water and you'd got to take some to put in to start the pump going again. How we used to do it, I - when I look back on it, would I do it 
again? No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What year was the first child born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh, Charlie was born 1923. 1922. I only had - I was married in September and he was born the following August. So I didn't have long really on my own. Although in these days - we got our home - to s
tart with, our furniture and everything to start with. It was a four roomed cottage and I'd got it all settled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Because it went with the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 The house went with the job but you had to have the furniture in it you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So with all these moves you always had to move the furniture as well did you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes. Oh yes. And - we'd only - only been married a week when we got - as I told you, I think I told you, when we got there - there was just our furniture, there was the two beds, and the two
 bedroom furniture, but no - our boxes hadn't arrived - with our spoons and forks and sheets and suchlike, tea cloth and etcetera. They were at the railway station, by the time we'd walked the three mile from the - railway station on the Saturday - it was
 
afternoon you see. And of course when we found our boxes - we thought naturally as young ones say, oh let's lay the line down first and - then suchlike, and we did that and we had something to eat. Then it come - bedtime. After tea. We'd better go and mak
e
 the beds. Where's the sheets. The boxes haven't arrived. So of course we had to walk all the way back again, it started raining. Had to walk all the way back to the Kings Langley. I don't know whether you've heard of Kings Langley. Walk back to Kings Lan
g
ley and of course the guard there, the chap in the railway station said, oh we can't open the - goods yard anymore, not 'til Monday morning. Said, what are we going to do then? So - anyway there was a very kind - village store, sells - Post Office cumever
y
thing, to a sewing needle. And they were good, he lent us a lamp, he lent us a - paraffin, two knives and forks, two cups and saucers. I said, we can always do with cups and saucers so we went take those back. And - a kettle. You know, just lent us enough
 for the weekend. So my husband could - borrow a cart from the farm to go down Monday morning and bring - well we slept between two mattresses for the weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Did you ever wish you could have had another job, when you were working was there ever a job or career you feel you would have liked to have had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, dairy work. Dairy work. I should love to have taken - if I hadn't had the children, and my health was all right, I should have kept on with -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You really liked that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, I liked
 that - making butter and - separating and - bottling and all that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 In any of your jobs did you ever belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. Since I was - when I was - after I was married I worked at Cromptons for a little while in Chelmsford, part time, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that after the dairy work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, after I was married, oh I - yes, just recently. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Since the last war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, yes. Oh about - that'd be about - we've been up here - four - eight - about twenty years ago that'd be. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 How long did you stay there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Part time? Well I didn't stay there for long. 'Cos that was too much for me. But - doctor - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You were there less than a year too do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes. Yes. But - it was all right, I didn't mind 
it. That was canteen work, that was canteen work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Serving up the food and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
That's right, yes. But - 'course that was - there was plenty in there, was - one, two, three - four cooks and - vegetable cook - another one'd be anoth
er cook for something else, pastry cook, and then in the - next - next section'd be the washing up section which'd be four girls in the washing up section, one on the washing machine, washing up machine, and two at the sink and another one piling up. And 
then there'd be four of us in the canteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was that serving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Serving and - doing the canteen - the counter down. Polishing and - 'cos all chrome plated you see and the - the urns and all that to be seen to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were there any other part time jobs you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. That was - that was - apart -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you never managed full time work again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. Oh no. No. Oh no. When you've got a family you can't do both - no, no, you can't, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were working did you feel that employers and 
workers had the same interests or different, the same sort of outlook or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh they didn't care as long as the work was done. You see. And - one thing there I remember - my money went in with my husband's. I never knew - knew what I earnt. Wh
ich I think was very unfair. Really. I think - if you're working you should have a separate pay pocket, don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Did you feel that there was a division of interest among workers themselves, that some workers had a different outlook from others? When
 you were in the factory for example did you feel that all the workers had the same kind of attitude to work and the employers
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, some didn't like the employers and some did, you see, oh yes. All depend on the employer, sometimes we had - nice - foremen and other times we didn't. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Would you say that full time work changed your attitude to life in any way? Thinking back particularly to when you were in service, do you think it changed your outlook on life at all, what you experienced in service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Well I don't know, I was always - always had to work you see and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You worked at the orphanage too of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh yes, had to work before you went to school even. You always had - all had your jobs to do before you went to - got ready for school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 So really going out to work wasn't such a change for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, not for me. No, no. I didn't have easy life. Like once you leave school - or you - or you start work you think oh you're going to have easy life in the evenings, well you didn't. You still had to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What time did you finish work with Miss Ellis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Miss Ellis? I always had to be in bed by half past nine. She was good that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 She didn't keep you up very late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 When you were there did you get to know any new friends, boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, we weren't allowed - I wasn't even allowed to go to the back door to the milkman. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Boyfriends would have been fro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11339072\charrsid675430 wn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 ed on would they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Any girl friends, did you ever go out with a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's where I met Nora.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You met her at Miss Ellis' did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, not at Miss Ellis'. I come in contact with - how did I come in contact with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 In one of your other places was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Ah yes, I 
went to another place, Miss - Tollits. He was J.P., that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
But you didn't have any new friends in that period up to the end of the first war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I didn't - didn't have any girl friends, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 What about friends from the orphanage, did you keep in touch with any of them?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Ah there was one or two used to go to a Bible class on a Sunday. And I was - that was once a month, and Miss Ellis used to let me go to that. That was on the Regent Road and I'd go straight there back. She al
ways used to time me. I had to be in by this certain time. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You'd see these old friends there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You didn't correspond with anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no. No. This - this person that took the Bible class, she was also on the committee of the orphanage. So of course her and Miss Ellis'd be in co naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
About your evenings out, how often were you allowed out while you were with Miss Ellis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh once a week. Was it once a week? Wait a minute, let me think. From four to six - and t
hen from six to eight. That's twice a week. Then on Sundays - Sunday morning - one - one Sunday it'd be Sunday morning, another - Sunday be Sunday afternoon and evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It alternated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you always got some time off on a Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 And you always got those two short spells?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Always had to be in by eight o'clock. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But you were allowed out on two evenings of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 But not for very long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No. No. No. Got to be there and back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Was there anything that you particularly liked or disliked about your position with Miss Ellis, in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Well when - spring cleaning. She used to have some lovely - lovely - ornaments - and things. I wasn't allowed to touch them. But I could watch Jessie - washing them and putting them back. Oh they were beautiful things, they must be worth - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You mean you liked the spring cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, I didn't mind that, I didn't mind the h
ard work, I got used to it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there anything you particularly disliked about being there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh she was - I didn't have long enough out. No - freedom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 You felt confined?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Yes, no freedom. And I used to have to wear long frocks and - oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
In that household was anything homemade, like bread or jam or pickles or wine or beer, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No, the only thing that - was there - Miss Ellis would always have - what do they call it now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Herb beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, in th
e - filtered water. Filtered water. Always filtered water. But - what is - the cook was very good at - soups. Very good at soups. She could make any - lovely soup. But apart from that - no, not making any jam or anything like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did they grow fruit and vegetables there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
No. No. Because they had to get rid of the gardener when the war came. He went you see. And it was all put down to lawns and roses then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Who looked after that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 That was the coachmen, when the horses went he
 took over the gardener's job you see. And the boy - just had a boy to help him, do the knives and suchlike. That was - when I saw knife machine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was any livestock kept at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Not there. Oh no. Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Was there meat eaten every day there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Meat? Oh I can't remember. Well I suppose - no, always had fish alternative I expect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 It was always meat or fish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Something, yes. Always cooked meal. Oh yes. Yes, midday always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Were you well fed there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes. Yes. But of c
ourse it was wartime and we didn't have much butter. Or anything like that, everything was rationed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did she use tinned meat at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 No, I don't think - don't remember. Don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Did you have the same food as she had or different food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Oh yes, we had the same food, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5178298 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 Even when she had that six course dinner and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9393546 NM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1707796\charrsid675430 
Oh no, we didn't have six courses, no, we just had the two. But we were served the same as her, more or less what she had.
